<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Hails British Decision to Resume Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid Thursday hailed the decision by the British
government to resume diplomatic relations with Libya.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by the league secretariat, Abdel-Meguid
expressed hope that Britain's decision would lead to the lifting
of sanctions on Libya due to the Lockerbie issue.
</P>
<P>
He said that the sanctions "have caused damage to the Libyan
people and its neighboring countries."
</P>
<P>
In 1988, a Pan AM flight was blown up over Lockerbie, Scotland,
leaving 270 people dead. Britain and the United States accused two
Libyans of masterminding the explosion and demanded that Tripoli
hand over the suspects for trial.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the U.S. pressed the U.N. Security Council to
impose an air and arms embargo on Libya in 1992 for its failure to
extradite the suspects.
</P>
<P>
Mediated by Saudi Arabia and South Africa, Libya handed over
the two suspects in April to a Scottish court in the
Netherlands. And the U.N. Security Council suspended the sanctions
according to a resolution adopted before the Libyan move.
</P>
<P>
Britain severed its diplomatic relations with Libya in 1984
after someone at the Libyan Embassy in London shot dead a British
policewoman, who was maintaining order in a protest against Libyan
leader Muammar Gaddafi outside the embassy.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said on Wednesday that the
British government decided to resume diplomatic ties with Libya
after the main issues affecting the bilateral ties have been
solved, especially Libya has promised to cooperate with Britain in
investigating the killing of the policewoman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
