<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- A United Nations employee accused by Iraq of
carrying out acts of sabotage in northern Iraq left Baghdad on
Thursday morning, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
INA said Ayan Broughton, known as Red, a New Zealander, left
Baghdad on Thursday morning and is on his way to Amman, Jordan
after it was proved that he carried out sabotage acts aimed at
harming Iraq's agriculture resources.
</P>
<P>
An official with the U.N. Office of Humanitarian Coordinator
in Iraq (UNOHCI) confirmed that Broughton had left Baghdad.
(BC-Iraq-UN-Sabotage)
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The United Nations Office of Humanitarian
Coordinator in Iraq (UNOHCI) on Thursday dismissed the Iraqi
accusation that a U.N. employee carried out acts of sabotage in
northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
UNOHCI said in a statement that "neither Ayan Broughton, nor
any other U.N.-related person was in the area identified by the
Iraqi authorities on April 8."
</P>
<P>
Iraq accused Broughton, known as Red, a New Zealander working
as a supervisor at the U.N. Office of Project Services which is
entrusted with removing land mines in northern Iraq's Suleimaniya
province, of attempting to spread agriculture pests on April 8.
(BC-Iraq-UN-Denial)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel sought to lower Arab expectations Thursday
prior to Prime Minister Ehud Barak's first peace initiative,
saying his planned meetings with Arab leaders are mainly designed
to build trust.
</P>
<P>
Three days after his swearing-in, Barak will travel to
Alexandria Friday to meet Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
kicking off a series of meetings with peace partners including
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat, Jordanian
King Abdullah and U.S. President Bill Clinton. (BC-Israel-Arab)
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- The Cyprus government Thursday expressed
dissatisfaction with a resolution adopted by the foreign ministers
of the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC), who met recently
in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
The OIC foreign ministers expressed "firm support for the
rightful cause of the Turkish Muslim people of Cyprus" in its
resolution.
</P>
<P>
While describing the resolution as "adverse," Cyprus government
spokesman Costas Serezis told the press that it was not the first
time the OIC had issued an unfavorable resolution on Cyprus and
this time "it went further." (BC-Cyprus-OIC) 
</P>
</TEXT>
