<HEADLINE> Feature: Nostalgia Arises From a Wine Glass </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A couple were sipping wine at a
road-side open-air restaurant. Zvanko Antic simply watched them
drinking. He could not afford to spend any of his remaining few
dinars on even a single glass of wine.
</P>
<P>
The man, who has spent 30 years of his life making wine in
southwestern Kosovo, was now hundreds of kilometers away from the
vineyard and brewery he used to work at. He stayed at a motel 20
kilometers outside Belgrade, as a refugee or internally displaced
person.
</P>
<P>
Along with him were 122 other people from the same region of
the Yugoslav province. The oldest of the group was 95 while the
youngest six months.
</P>
<P>
Half of the group was formed by children under the age of 14.
They travelled in five tractors and four family cars from their
villages around Prizren northward until they stopped at the motel,
known as Pension Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
They first thought that they had finally survived the NATO
bombing after the western military alliance stopped dropping
missiles and bombs in early June. But they were wrong.
</P>
<P>
Some Kosovo separatists set fires to the houses of Kosovo Serbs
who were thus forced to leave.
</P>
<P>
With no relatives to seek help from, the refugees ended up in
the motel in which they used mattresses made of chemical fabric as
cover and artificial foam as stuffing.
</P>
<P>
The 12 members of Zvanko's family included his parents, his
brother and sister-in-law and their six children ranging from two
to nine. They squeezed onto eight mattresses spread over a corner
of the dining hall of the motel.
</P>
<P>
Two other big families shared the same dining hall.
</P>
<P>
Upstairs in a guest room measuring three meters by four lived a
95-year-old man called Dragutinovic Dragutin.
</P>
<P>
The old man, one of the dozen who took part in the Salunski
battle of the First World War for Serbia and was still alive,
shared the room with his son and daughter-in-law, his grandson and
granddaughter-in-law and his great grandsons. Eight of them on
six mattresses.
</P>
<P>
Jovanovic Branislav was even less lucky. Due to the mismatch
of motel rooms and the number of refugees, he had to live in the
huts made of plastic sheet on the trailer behind his tractor.
</P>
<P>
Another adult also lived outside in another trailer.
</P>
<P>
Left with their houses on fire, these people grabbed whatever
they could before they set off on a journey nobody knew where it
would end.
</P>
<P>
They now got one hot meal each day from the student center of
the capital city and they had to make do with whatever they could
for the other two meals, be it cold bread, cold pancakes or
sometimes nothing to eat with.
</P>
<P>
Each and every family of the group had to carefully calculate
to make their remaining money last longer. They never dared to
think that they could raise 10,000 German marks to arrange a heart
correction operation for 16-month-old Momirka Ilic of their group.
</P>
<P>
After NATO stopped bombing, the Yugoslav authorities appealed
the Kosovo Serbs to return to their homes in the province.
</P>
<P>
Already knowing that they had no place to return to, these
refugees asked that how could they be expected to return to a
place that is not secure even with an international security force
present.
</P>
<P>
Zvanko said that who would not be nostalgic after leaving his
native land for so long. When asked whether he used to drink wine
in his hometown, he replied it was only commonplace to drink wine
in a place that has best been known for its wine producing repute.
"It is like drinking water," said he with an imaginery glass
lifted toward his lips.
</P>
<P>
The man said that with last season's produce still in the wine
cellar and no one was at home to attend this season's production,
how could they be expected to return with no money left.
</P>
<P>
Zvanko, whose forefathers lived in Kosovo for centuries, said
that in his family was left 300 liters of family-made wine behind
and there were 12 million German mark worth of red wine, white
wine and brandy left in the vinery he used to work in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Watching the couple drinking away, Zvanko said that the wine
made him all the more homesick. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
