<HEADLINE> N.Irish Protestant March Banned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland authorities on
Thursday banned the Protestant Orange Order from holding a major
demonstration on July 12 near a Roman Catholic area in Belfast.
</P>
<P>
The independent Parades Commission said the order's plans to
gather in a park near the mostly Catholic Lower Ormeau Road area
risked sparking sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
Commission head Alistair Graham told a news conference the
demonstration could have involved up to 20,000 Orangemen, bandsmen
and their supporters.
</P>
<P>
"It is bound therefore to bring problems, major problems of
disruption, tension and damage to fragile community
relationships," Reuters quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Orange Order planned the demonstration after it was earlier
banned from marching directly through the Lower Ormeau Road area
on July 12, a day celebrated by Protestants for centuries-old
battlefield victories over Catholics.
</P>
<P>
The new ban came as Britain and the Irish Republic stepped up
efforts to get feuding politicians from the British province's
Protestant majority and Catholic minority to end a deadlock over
guerrilla disarmament that has paralysed the peace process. They
have set July 15 as a new deadline for a deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
