<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets in Mixed Finale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON July 8 (Xinhua) - European bourses ended mixed Thursday
as London and Paris closed lower in reaction to an opening slide
on Wall Street, while Frankfurt gained on the strength of
financial issues.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 ended the session down 40.1, or 0.61 percent,
at 6557.3 despite almost unanimous predictions that the Bank of
England's lending rate would not change.
</P>
<P>
The fallers included most of the high-street banks, with
Barclays down 38 pence to 1821p, NatWest down 40p to 1332p and
Lloyds down 14p to 841p.
</P>
<P>
Oil stocks were the one bright spot in the market, with both
Shell and BP Amoco edging up on the back of rising oil prices,
adding 15 points to the FTSE index.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC 40 closed down 31.07 points at 4631.13, a
fall of 0.67 percent, led by bond market weakness and selling
pressures on three of the issues involved in oil and banking
takeover battles.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt's Xetra Dax closed 18.60 points higher at 5607.10, a
gain of 0.33 percent, buoyed by a strong run among banking stocks.
</P>
<P>
Dresdner Bank added 2.51 euros to 43.01 euros, while Deutsche
Bank was up 4.75 percent at 64.16. Commerzbank was 1.26 euros
firmer at 33.26.
</P>
<P>
Car shares also performed quite strongly. BMW finished 12.49
euros higher at 719.49, and Volkswagen gained 0.74 at 62.05.
</P>
</TEXT>
