<HEADLINE> Euro Hits New low but off Lows in London </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The euro fell to yet another record
low against the dollar Thursday after comments from Germany's
finance minister convinced traders that central banks would not
step in to prevent the currency's fall.
</P>
<P>
The euro fell to a new life low of 1.0149 U.S. dollars, down
from around 1.018 U.S. dollars before German Finance Minister Hans
Eichel said its weakness was not a problem because it boosted
German exports. But it recovered some ground late in the European
day.
</P>
<P>
Traders took Eichel's comments, made during a visit to Denmark,
to mean that European central banks were in no hurry to support
the currency.
</P>
<P>
"When you have Eichel saying it (the weak euro) is helping
Euroland growth, it is a red rag to a bear as far as the euro is
concerned," a Reuters reported quoted Steve Barrow, currency
strategist at Bear Stearns in London, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, by midday in the U.S. traders were again
wondering if European central banks might intervene to prop up the
euro as it neared parity with the dollar. A market rumor that
Germany's central bank had asked commercial banks to stay open
after hours fueled intervention speculation and the euro popped
back up above 1.02 U.S. dollars, compared with 1.0220 U.S. dollars
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Euro zone government bond prices fell again in tandem with
drops in the euro against the dollar, and traders saw potential
for further falls.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark 10-year German Bund saw its yield rise quickly to
4.85 percent from around 4.2 percent just three weeks ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
