<HEADLINE> Poverty, Major Cause for Conflicts in Africa: UN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Poverty is one of the key factors
that leads to the unrest and wars in Africa, a senior U.N.
official said here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of OAU's 70th ordinary session
of the Council of Ministers in Algerian capital Algiers, Kingsly
Amoako, U.N. Undersecretary-General and Executive Secretary of the
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), said that at least four
hypotheses have been advanced to explain the cause of civil wars
in the continent.
</P>
<P>
The first factor, Amoako said, is the innate ethnic and
religious hatred, where these hatreds are then exploited by
ambitious leaders.
</P>
<P>
Poverty is inextricably related to conflicts, particularly when
the lack of human capital becomes a viable employment opportunity
where job markets do not incorporate youth, he said.
</P>
<P>
The national grievance, where the performance of a government
is held to be against the national interests, is regarded as the
second one behind the unrest and conflicts in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Employment, when taken as a motivation for gains of capturing
the resources, is also seen by the U.N. official as one of the
roots for instability and armed conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Poverty, which often leads to war in the continent, is costly
when natural resources are not managed equitably and governments
are not democratic and societies are polarized, he added.
</P>
<P>
"War is undoubtedly the destroyer of economic development on
our continent," Amoako noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that regional organizations should play a leading role
in ensuring cooperation among states and in guiding support from
the international community toward sustained and durable peace in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
OAU's Council of Ministers meet twice a year to discuss, among
other things, the organization's annual budget and make
preparations for the annual OAU summit.
</P>
<P>
The OAU was founded on June 25 of 1963 to promote unity and
solidarity among independent African countries. It had 32 members
when established and now has 53 member states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
