<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Union Assists 80,000 Serbian Jobless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Serbian Trade Union Federation
(SSS) has so far offered financial assistance to 80,000 Serbian
jobless people.
</P>
<P>
Local press quoting the trade union said on Thursday that the
SSS in cooperation with the Federal Labor Ministry offered aid to
those people rendered jobless by NATO bombing against Yugoslavia
between March 24 and June 9.
</P>
<P>
SSS Secretary Slobodan Jovanovic was quoted as saying that the
NATO bombing-caused jobless people were getting a minimum monthly
wage of 230 dinars (20 U.S. dollars) along with their pension and
healthcare payments.
</P>
<P>
The financial assistance will be available for three months.
</P>
<P>
The SSS secretary said that 100,000 workers in Serbia alone
were made jobless as a direct result of NATO bombing which made
about half a million jobless further down the production chain.
</P>
<P>
Some of the factories have been trying to start production in
order to help solve the NATO bombing-caused unemployment problem,
according to the secretary.  
</P>
</TEXT>
