<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-08 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatari Emir Meets Saudi Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Saudi Defense and
Aviation Minister Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul Aziz held talks Thursday
with Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani on bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also discussed issues concerning the march of
the Gulf Arab nations and the latest regional developments,
according to reports by Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the visit by Sultan, also Saudi second deputy
prime minister and general inspector, bolstered ties between Doha
and Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi defense chief arrived in Qatar earlier in the day
from the United Arab Emirates (UAE), the first stop of his
four-nation Gulf tour which will later take him to Bahrain and
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
He canceled his visit to Oman due to the absence of Sultan
Qaboos Bin Sayed who is on a private visit abroad.
</P>
<P>
Since Sultan is making the trip to the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) states five days after GCC foreign ministers
concluded a meeting aimed at closing differences among member
states over a GCC-Iranian rapprochement, the visit is believed to
be a show of solidarity of alliance.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance
established in 1981, comprises Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar,
Saudi Arabia and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers agreed during their gathering to form a
tripartite committee, comprising Saudi Arabia, Qatar and Oman, to
solve the dispute between the UAE and Iran over three Gulf islands.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also reaffirmed their support for the UAE's
sovereignty over the islands of Abu Moussa, Greater and Lesser
Tunbs, which are now controlled by Iran.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dhabi recently voiced dismay over the warming up of ties
between some GCC states, headed by Saudi Arabia, and Iran, fearing
the rapprochement would undermine the GCC support for the UAE in
the dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
