<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Portuguese-speaking Parliamentarians to Meet in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique said Thursday that the
second forum of parliament heads from the Community of
Portuguese-Speaking States will be held in Mozambican capital
Maputo next week.
</P>
<P>
Alcido Nguenha, member of the Permanent Committee of the
Mozambican Parliament, said at a press conference here that the
forum is aimed to strengthen the cooperation among the parliaments
of the Portuguese-speaking states.
</P>
<P>
The Community of Portuguese-Speaking States comprises seven
countries, namely Angola, Brazil, Cape Verde, Guinea Bissau,
Mozambique, Portugal and Sao Tome and Principe.
</P>
<P>
The forum will also discuss the challenges the member states
are facing in the globalization process and the future of
democracy, said Nguenha.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentarians will also exchange experiences in the
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Angola, Brazil, Cape Verde, Guinea Bissau and Portugal have
confirmed their attendance while only Sao Tome and Principe has
not decided whether to attend or not.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentarian forum was established in Portuguese capital
Lisbon in 1998. The current chair of the forum is held by
Portugal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
