<HEADLINE> Kenya Safe for Visitors: Tourist Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- All tourists and other visitors are
assured that it is safe and secure when they visit Kenya and the
capital Nairobi, the Kenya Tourist Board said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tourists and visitors to the country "should feel free to come
and enjoy the cool July and August temperatures," the board said
in a statement issued after the privately-owned public vehicles
known as "matatu" strike Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As the strike entered its second day, the board said, Kenyan
capital Nairobi was calm and that people were going about their
businesses as usual.
</P>
<P>
"Whether the strike will go on is unclear, what is clear,
however, is that Nairobi is safe and Kenya is safe." the board
said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the strike was only affecting commuters who have
to make use of matatus or mini-buses as means of public transport
and did not affect visitors to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The board also mentioned that visitors from most countries of
the world do not need visas if they are coming for less than 30
days, saying that those tourists already in Kenya are encouraged
to relax and enjoy their holidays.
</P>
<P>
Matatus went on strike Wednesday in protest against the
introduction of the new regulations by the Transport Licensing
Board aiming at streamlining the matatu industry in the country.
</P>
<P>
The strikers, mainly touts, attempted to disrupt the smooth
flow of traffic by burning tires in the middle of some roads
leading to the cities, including capital Nairobi and Nakuru, the
country's third largest city in the central region.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulations, the matatu touts are to be
replaced by civic council workers at bus terminuses while matatu
drivers and conductors should wear identification badges, all
matatus are to be licensed by the board and matatu routes are to
be re-allocated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
