<HEADLINE> Cyprus Unhappy With OIC Resolution on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government Thursday
expressed dissatisfaction with a resolution adopted by the foreign
ministers of the Organization of Islamic Conference (OIC), who met
recently in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
Thew OIC foreign ministers expressed "firm support for the
rightful cause of the Turkish Muslim people of Cyprus" in its
resolution.
</P>
<P>
While describing the resolution as "adverse," Cyprus government
spokesman Costas Serezis told the press that it was not the first
time the OIC had issued an unfavorable resolution on Cyprus and
this time "it went further."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Cyprus government was taking necessary
measures through diplomatic channels on the matter.
</P>
<P>
The organization also reaffirmed its solidarity with the
Turkish Cypriots and "called for a just political settlement with
respect to the legitimate aspirations of the Turkish Cypriots."
</P>
<P>
It stressed that implementing a proposal, presented by Turkish
Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash in 1998, for the establishment of
confederation of two states in Cyprus holds the key to a political
and viable settlement of the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. is pushing for reunification of Cyprus under a
bi-communal, bi-zonal federation formula but all efforts have so
far failed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
