<HEADLINE> Summers Warns Not to Become Overconfident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States can't become
overconfident, and markets must be opened and exports promoted,
new Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers warned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. economy is on a course to allow workers wage increases
that exceed inflation, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we can keep our fundamentals strong and continue the
terrific productivity improvement, I think we have got room to
give people wage increases that run ahead of price increases and
represent really higher standards of living," Summers said on
NBC's "Today" in his seventh day as new Treasury chief.
</P>
<P>
He said the right course for the economy was set during the
tenure of his predecessor Robert Rubin at the Treasury Department.
</P>
<P>
"Our challenge is to carry on," Summers said. "I think we are
going to be able to do that under President Clinton's leadership,
to keep paying down that federal debt, to put in place a framework
for the beginning of the next century, when, I think, our country
is going to be in a much, much stronger economic position than
anyone thought likely a few years ago."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, he signalled steady U.S. economic priorities on a
strong dollar and urged both Europe and Japan to boost their
domestic demand.  
</P>
</TEXT>
