<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's leading air carrier Mexicana
de Aviacion is slated to become the tenth member of the "Star
Alliance" of airlines, Deutsche Lufthansa announced Thursday in
Frankfurt.
</P>
<P>
Mexicana would join the Star Alliance in 2000, which would add
new destinations in Mexico and Latin America available to
customers flying with the alliance's air companies, Lufthansa
said.
</P>
<P>
Mexicana de Aviacion was founded in 1921 and now carries some
eight million passengers a year, serving 32 destinations in
Mexico, eight in the United States, two in Canada, three in
Central America, five in South America and one in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Star Alliance was set up in 1997. At the moment, some 32
million passengers now use the Star Alliance airlines each year.
</P>
<P>
Star Alliance currently consists of Lufthansa, Air Canada, Air
New Zealand, Ansett Australia, Scandinavian Airlines System, Thai
Airways International, United Airlines and Varig Brazilian
Airlines. All Nippon Airways is due to link into the alliance in
October.  
