<HEADLINE> U.S. Not trying to Block IMF Funding to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States will not try to
block Zimbabwe's funding from the International Monetary Fund
(IMF), visiting U.S. Congressmen said in Harare Thursday.
</P>
<P>
California Republican Tom Campell and New Jersey Democrat
Donald Payne dismissed reports that the U.S. was interfering in
the disbursement of the long-awaited 53 million U.S. dollars
balance of payment support to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"Implications that we are blocking IMF funding to Zimbabwe are
not true. We are encouraging that Zimbabwe will resolve with the
IMF anything outstanding," Campell said during a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. had always been supportive for Zimbabwe and
wanted it to make good economic decisions.
</P>
<P>
He also said he supported the forgiveness of debts to poor
countries because they were incurred by previous regimes which
they had no control over.
</P>
<P>
Payne said although Zimbabwe had tremendous potential, it had
undergone several economic problems.
</P>
<P>
He said they were pleased the involvement in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) was coming to an end following the signing
of a peace agreement by the warring parties.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congressmen who were expected to leave for home
Thursday were on a fact-finding mission in the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
During their visit to Zimbabwe, they met with Zimbabwean
President Robert Mugabe and discussed regional issues related to
security, trade and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The IMF suspended aid to Zimbabwe last August because of
concerns over the Zimbabwean government's policies, price controls
on essential goods, Zimbabwe's involvement in the DRC and the slow
pace of selling loss-making state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
However, Mugabe has lambasted the IMF, saying that it could
keep its aid if it continued to attach conditions before releasing
the funds. 
</P>
