<HEADLINE> Greece's Inflation Reduces to 2.1 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Greece' consumer price inflation
dropped from 2.4 percent in May to 2.1 percent in June, the
National Statistics Service (NSS) announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The inflation trend would depend on the impact of rising fuel
prices in international markets, the NSS said, adding that
developments in the domestic market were satisfactory particularly
in fruit and vegetables prices.
</P>
<P>
Greece's consumer price index rose 3.8 percent in June still
far from a target of 2.3-2.2 percent for the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
In April, Greece's consumer price index rose 2.8 percent on the
year from a rise of 3.4 percent in March, falling below 3 percent
for the first time since 1971.
</P>
<P>
Greece aims to join the European Economic and Monetary Union
(EMU) in January 2001, but inflation is seen as the toughest
hurdle for the country to take in its progress towards its
accession to EMU.
</P>
<P>
Under the Maastricht criteria, inflation should be no more than
1.5 percentage points above the average inflation of the three
European Union (EU) best-performing nations.
</P>
<P>
In order to contain the increases of fuel prices, Greece's
Development Ministry and the oil trade companies have agreed to
split by half the burden of price rises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
