<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP to Release New Report on Globalization and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A new report, which is to be
released by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP) on July
12, shows how the forces of globalization have generated
unprecedented wealth for those who have been able to take
advantage of the increasing flow of goods and services across
national boundaries.
</P>
<P>
But globalization, as it has been allowed to proceed so far,
has also been driving a deeper wedge between richer and many poor
countries, and among people within countries, UNDP officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
People in some 85 countries are in fact worse off in many
respects than they were a decade ago, according to the 1999 Human
Development Report.
</P>
<P>
The challenge is to ensure that the benefits of globalization
are shared equitably, the report says. Globalization can be made
"to work for people as well as for profits."
</P>
<P>
The report, produced by an independent group of scholars and
development experts for UNDP, also ranks 174 countries according
to their level of human development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
