<HEADLINE> Sino-Tanzanian Joint Medicine Plant Soon in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa Thursday praised China's continuous aid to his country while
inspecting a Sino-Tanzanian joint medicine factory that will soon
go into operation.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzansino United Pharmaceuticals (T) Ltd. factory on the
suburb of capital Dar es Salaam is expected to produce about one
billion tablets and 200 million capsules annually worth two
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 1.85-million-dollar project, invested by China and Tanzania
with a ratio of 55 percent and 45 percent, produces mainly
medicine to treat epidemic diseases in Africa such as cholera,
malaria and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa told factory staff that he hoped this joint venture would
set a good example to attract more Chinese investment to deepen
bilateral economic cooperation between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang Haibin, General Manager of the plant,
beginning in November 1997, the factory has been designed and
constructed strictly in line with the international Good
Manufacturing Practice (GMP), the first of its kind in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
The factory is expected to be commercially operational soon
after going through all necessary quality and environmental
processes. 
</P>
