<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Needs Faster Growth to Eradicate Poverty: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Undersecretary-General Kingsly Amoako said Thursday Africa needs
developing faster in order to be really integrated with the
outside world.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official made the comment when addressing the opening
ceremony of the 70th ordinary session of OAU's Council of
Ministers here this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"Without exception, the countries in the region are growing at
less than 7 percent per annum, the rate needed for Africa to meet
the international development target of reducing poverty in half
by the year 2015," said Amoako.
</P>
<P>
What is more, there are significant sub-regional differences in
Africa's growth performance, he added.
</P>
<P>
Of the five sub-regions in the continent, only two, accounting
for only about 25 percent of the continent's population, enjoyed a
positive growth performance.
</P>
<P>
Growth decelerated in the remaining three sub-regions where the
 overwhelming 75 percent of the population reside.
</P>
<P>
He attributed the drastic sub-regional difference in growth
performance to the incidence of war and civil unrest.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, 32 countries in Africa experienced some improvement
while 17 were worse off at the start of 1999 than they had been
one year before.
</P>
<P>
More than half of Africa's population are still living under
the poverty line, and wars and unrest are held responsible for
millions of refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
