<HEADLINE> Annan Welcomes Adoption of Congo Cease-Fire Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan has prepared to deploy United Nations military observers at
an early date to the Democratic Republic of the Congo ahead of a
full-scale U.N. peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
Annan, now touring Africa, expressed the readiness in a
statement issued through his spokesman at the U.N. Headquarters in
New York late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement was issued after African defense and foreign
ministers adopted in Lusaka on Wednesday a cease-fire agreement
for the Democratic Republic of the Congo, former Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"This is an important and welcome step towards the restoration
of peace in the Democratic Republic of the Congo and in the Great
Lakes region of Africa," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General urged the governments and rebel leaders
concerned to sign and ratify the cease-fire agreement as a matter
of urgency and called on them to enact an immediate cessation of
hostilities and troops standstill, pending the entry into force of
the pact.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations will spare no effort in mobilizing the
international community to assist the peoples of the region in
their efforts to achieve reconciliation, reconstruction and
development," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. technical survey team is being dispatched to Kinshasa
this week to assess the feasibility of deploying observers,
according Annan's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief was winding up his stay in Senegal, the first
leg of his Africa journey which takes him also to Sierra Leone,
Liberia, Guinea, Nigeria and Algeria.  
</P>
