<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Human Rights Commission Special Rapporteur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Special
Rapporteur on human rights in Bosnia and Herzegovina, Croatia and
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, Jiri Dientsbier, begins a
five-day visit to Kosovo, a Yugoslav province, Thursday, U.N.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, which will end on july 12, the special
rapporteur is scheduled to meet the acting U.N. special
representative in Kosovo, Sergio Vieira de Mello, and other
members of the United Nations Interim Administration Mission in
Kosovo, known as UNMIK.
</P>
<P>
Dientsbier, who was appointed special rapporteur by the U.N.
Commission on Human Rights last year, is also expected to meet
with Lt.-General Michael Jackson, commander of the peackeepers in
Kosovo (KFOR), and Daan Everts, head of the Kosovo mission of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to his visit to Pristina, provincial capital of
Kosovo, the special rapporteur is to travel to the Pec and Prizren
districts in the Serbian province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
