<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Lebanese Premier Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Former Lebanese Prime Minister
Chafic al-Wazzan, 74, died of a heart attack Thursday, a
statement of prime minister's palace said.
</P>
<P>
Wazzan's funeral will be held on Friday, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Public institutions' flag across Lebanon will fly at half-mast
and radio and television stations will broadcast
non-entertainment programs for three days, according to the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Wazzan served as head of the Lebanese government from 1980 to
1984.
</P>
<P>
During his tenure, Israel launched the second massive invasion
of Lebanon with the declared aim of finally eliminating the
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO)'s military threat to
Israel's northern border.
</P>
<P>
The PLO led by Yasser Arafat, which was then stationed in south
Lebanon to launch attacks on northern Israel, was forced to leave
the country for Algeria, Tunisia and Yemen when Wazzan was in
office.
</P>
<P>
He resigned after the country's conflicting factions failed to
reach an accord to end the 15-year civil war which erupted in
1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Parliament Head to Persuade Belgrade to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Greek Parliament President Apostolos
Kaklamanis on Thursday voiced his willingness to persuade
Yugoslavia to release the two Australians imprisoned as spies.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after talks with visiting Speaker of the Australian
House of Representatives Neil Andrew, Kaklamanis said that he
would mediate with his Yugoslav counterpart for an early release
of the two Australian aid workers charged by Belgrade of spying
for the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Andrew, who is heading a large cross-party delegation, thanked
Greece for its continuing efforts to have the two Australians
released.
</P>
<P>
Steve Pratt and Peter Wallace, part of Care Australia's refugee
relief program in Yugoslavia, were jailed for 12 years and four
years respectively after being arrested on Yugoslavia's border
with Croatia on March 31.
</P>
<P>
Greece urged Belgrade in April to release the two men as a
humanitarian measure, but Belgrade failed to do so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
