<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Winds Delay U.S. Boeing Rocket Launch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Boeing company Thursday
delayed the launch of a Delta 2 rocket carrying four satellites
for the Globalstar worldwide mobile phone network because of high
altitude winds.
</P>
<P>
Lift off of the Boeing-built booster was rescheduled for Friday
morning in Cape Canaveral in Florida State.
</P>
<P>
The rocket was to place into orbit four satellites for
Globalstar, an international consortium led by Loral Space and
Communications.
</P>
<P>
Globalstar needs 32 orbiting satellites for the planned start
of its commercial phone service in September. The U.S. Delta and
Russian Soyuz rockets have already launched 24 of the spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
Calls can be made with hand-held phones from virtually anywhere
in the world when the Globalstar system is operational. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
