<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. New Jobless Claims Fall While Retail Sales Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department said
Thursday the number of new claims for unemployment benefits
dropped last week to the lowest level in more than three months.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most of the nation's largest retailers said that
their June sales rose to better-than-expected levels.
</P>
<P>
June's strong retail sales, which followed big gains in
May,were attributed to the hefty U.S. economy and
warmer-than-normal weather that sent shoppers into stores for
everything from bathing suits to air conditioners.
</P>
<P>
According to the Department's report, 294,000 people filed new
claims for jobless benefits for the week ending July 3, down by
6,000 from the previous week. Last week's level was the lowest
since 289,000 in the week ending March 27.
</P>
<P>
The four-week moving average for claims, which smoothes out
week-to-week volatility, also was down to 299,000, the lowest
level since April 3, when they were at 296,500.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the remaining low jobless claims applications
reflect an extremely tight labor market, on which the Federal
Reserve is keeping a watchful eye. 
</P>
</TEXT>
