<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sao Tome Foreign Minister Tenders Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Sao Tome and Principe Foreign
Minister Alberto Paulino Thursday formally handed in his
resignation to Prime Minister Guilherme Posser da Costa, the
Angolan News Agency Angop reported.
</P>
<P>
Posser confirmed this but he stressed that he would discuss the
matter with President Miguel Trovoada because the president has
his say in the appointment or dismissal of the foreign minister or
defense minister according to the constitution of the republic.
</P>
<P>
Paulino was reluctant to comment on his intention to resign,
only attributing it to his own health condition and the prime
minister's intention to reshuffle the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Posser admitted that he intends to reshuffle his cabinet,
saying that he would do so in a bid to improve the performance of
the government departments.
</P>
<P>
Paulino has been the second minister tendering a resignation
since the Posser administration came into being early this year.
</P>
<P>
The scandal of illegally issuing 500-million-U.S. dollar
treasury bills forced former minister of planning, finance and
cooperation, Afonso Varela, to resign on March 25. He was
replaced by Adelino Castelo David. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean, DRC Presidents Hold Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 8 (Xinhua) -- President Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe
and visiting President Laurent Kabila of the Democratic Republic
of Congo (DRC) held private consultation talks in Harare Thursday
on the latest situation in the war-torn DRC.
</P>
<P>
After the five-hour talks, Mugabe told reporters that they
discussed the outcome of a peace deal signed by African defense
and foreign affairs ministers who were holding talks in Zambian
capital Lusaka Wednesday to seek for an end to the 11-month war in
the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said he had not been told yet by mediator in the crisis,
Zambian President Fredrick Chiluba, on when a meeting by heads of
states would be held to sign the document.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Chiluba reportedly said Thursday that heads
of state would ratify the draft agreement at gathering in Lusaka
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"In negotiations, you can't get everything you want. We hope
all parties are genuine," said Mugabe referring to the Lusaka
draft cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the peace plan provides for a cease-fire
24 hours after the signing, the withdrawal of foreign troops, the
cessation of all military activities, the creation of a new
national army and the release of prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
The draft cease-fire document aimed at ending the war between
the allied forces helping Kabila troops and the rebels allegedly
backed by Rwanda and Uganda is now awaiting to be signed by heads
of the states which have been sucked in the war.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and Chad had sent troops fighting
alongside Kabila's soldiers to fend off the rebels who are
reported to be holding vast areas of land in eastern side of the
mineral-rich country.
</P>
<P>
The talks between Mugabe and Kabila were also attended by two
DRC senior government officials, Zimbabwean Vice-President Simon
Muzenda, Zimbabwean Defence Forces Commander Vitalis Zvinavashe
and Foreign Affairs Minister Stan Mudenge.
</P>
<P>
Kabila left here for home on the same day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
