<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Immediate Start of Disarming S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Thursday in Sierra Leone urged the country to immediately
start the disarming process under the newly assigned peace accord,
a report reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who paid the war-torn state a short visit Thursday,
promised the U.N. help in bringing in a lasting peace for the
long-suffered Sierra Leoneans.
</P>
<P>
Annan said there was "an immediate need for ECOMOG (the west
African peace-keeping force) and military observers to move very
quickly, for the rebel troops and militia to disarm and to be
directed to more productive activities."
</P>
<P>
"I can promise you that the U.N. can work hand in glove with
the government to bring peace about, but we all have to pool our
efforts. No one can do it alone," he told a press conference held
in Sierra Leonean capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
He added that some U.N. refugee organizations would soon resume
their work on bringing the war-created refugees back to their
homes.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief said that he was happy to be in Sierra Leone
only one day after a peace accord was assigned in Togolese capital
Lome.
</P>
<P>
Annan arrived in Freetown from Dakar, capital of Senegal. He
was due to spend a few hours in Monrovia, capital of Liberia
Thursday before flying to Guinea, and then visit Nigeria Saturday
before leaving for Algerian capital Algiers to attend the
Organization of African Unity Summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
