<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana's Economy on Right Track: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- An independent research body
Thursday commended the Ghanaian government for the tremendous
improvement in the country's economic management, the Ghana News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In its 1998 State of the Ghanaian Economy Report, the Ghana
Institute of Statistical, Social and Economic Research of the
University of Ghana said with a 4.6 percent gross domestic product
(GDP) growth, it was "heart warming" to find end-of-year inflation
at 15.7 percent, down from 20.8 percent at the beginning of 1998
and 70.8 percent at the end of 1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ghana Statistical Service, inflation was 9.4
percent in May this year.
</P>
<P>
Kwadwo Asenso-Okyere, Director of the economic research
institute, attributed the reduction in inflation to the moderate
growth in money supply of 17.3 percent last year as against 39.5
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said the Ghanaian currency Cedi was stable in 1998 with a
relative depreciation of just 4.2 percent in the inter-bank
market and 3.9 percent at the forex market.
</P>
<P>
Looking at the fiscal performance of the economy last year,
Asenso- Okyere said, the overall budget deficit in 1998 was about
6.3 percent of the GDP as compared with a projected 7.9 percent
for the year and 8.6 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said the low budget deficit resulted from better expenditure
 monitoring and control in 1998 than in previous years.
</P>
<P>
Asenso-Okyere said government expenditure on salaries and
wages continue to decline as a proportion of recurrent
expenditure, adding that the proportion had gone down from 90
percent in the 1980s to 33.5 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
He was happy about the performance of industry, service and
manufacturing sectors and emphasized that more efforts be put in
to make the situation get better.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the economy could have done better if it
were not for some external shocks experienced last year.
</P>
<P>
Giving the outlook for 1999, Asenso-Okyere said care must be
taken not to run the country into a recession, adding that other
indicators like unemployment must be watched closely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
