<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno
said Thursday the Justice Department is trying to decide whether
to investigate a group linked to a white supremacist who killed
two minority people.
</P>
<P>
Reno, speaking at a weekly press briefing, said the department
had not made the decision yet on whether to investigate the World
Church of the Creator, a group which espouses anti-minority views.
</P>
<P>
Smith, 21, a member of the group, killed two men and wounded
eight, all blacks, Asians and Orthodox Jews, in a recent three-day
shooting spree in Illinois and Indiana.
</P>
<P>
He killed himself in a hijacked van on the highway in Illinois
as the police closed in on him for arrest.
</P>
<P>
Reno, who was "appalled" to hear the shooting incident, said
the Justice Department must have "a reasonable indication of
criminal conduct" by the group before it can investigate it.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) and the Justice are
paying special attention to the group's activities to determine
whether it promotes violence by its members, officials say.
</P>
<P>
The group's leader, Matt Hale, claimed that his group is
nonviolent and uses "persuasion" to accomplish its goal of
promoting the white race.
</P>
<P>
Smith was seen distributing racist pamphlets when he was a
member of the World Church of the Creator.  
