<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Borrowing Shows Sharp Rise in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumers' credit
outstanding, excluding mortgage debt, grew sharply at a 10.9
percent annual rate in May to a seasonally adjusted 1.34 trillion
dollars, the Federal Reserve said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In May, consumers borrowed 12.1 billion dollars more than the
month before. The sharp increase in borrowing rate follows much
smaller gains in April and March and marked the largest increase
since January when consumer credit climbed at an annualized rate
of 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
In April, total credit outstanding rose at an annual rate of
just 0.4 percent, much less than the Fed previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
The Fed said May's increase was led by demand for non-revolving
loans, which rose at an annual rate of 15.7 percent. That category
includes loans for autos, mobile homes, boats, trailers, education
and vacations. It was the biggest increase for non-revolving
credit since January when it rose at an annual rate of 17.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Revolving credit -- primarily credit cards -- also went up in
May to an annual rate of 4.4 percent. That follows a bigger gain
of 5.9 percent rate in April.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said strong consumers' borrowing is a reflection of a
healthy economy. Owing to the robust consumer spending, the U.S.
economy is growing. At present, both inflation and unemployment
are low while consumer confidence is high and the stock market is
continuing to post record gains.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's report of consumer credit is the first one in which
the Fed stopped breaking out automobile loans as a separate
category. It's also the first report without a separate catchall
category that lumped loans for things including education,
vacations, mobile homes and boats.
</P>
<P>
These two categories, instead, are now folded into one called
nonrevolving credit. The Fed explained that it was going to a
larger category because it didn't trust the month-by-month
reliability of the previous smaller breakdowns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
