<HEADLINE> China's Customs Revenue Above Target in First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China's customs revenue amounted to
78.36 billion yuan (9.44 billion US dollars) in the first half of
this year, accounting for 93.4 percent of the target for the whole
year, according to information released today by the General
Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
Among the total, 1.79 billion yuan were spent on policy-related
tax refunds, and 76.57 billion yuan was passed to the state tax
coffers, up 117 percent from the corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Officials here attributed the rise to the country's fierce
fight against smuggling since last July, which helped halt illegal
channels of imports and increase imports through general trade in
the first six months by 80 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the customs department has stepped up efforts to
crack down on tax evasion, which added 8 billion yuan to the tax
collection figures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
