<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Schroeder Ends Ukraine Visit After Signing of Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During the visit, Schroeder held talks with Ukrainian President
Leonid Kuchma and Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko to exchange
views on promoting the development of bilateral economic
cooperation, the shutdown of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant and
joint participation in the reconstruction of Yugoslavia after NATO
's 78-day bombardment.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, Kuchma said that his country will do it can to
improve the investment environment and expressed the hope that
Germany will increase its direct investment in Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said that regular high-level consultations and
political contacts between the two countries will promote the
development of mutual economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Germany is Ukraine's second largest trade partner only after
Russia. Trade turnover between Germany and Ukraine totaled less
than 2 billion U.S. dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the controversial Chernobyl nuclear power plant,
Kuchma reaffirmed that Ukraine will act to close it down by 2000
as long as the Group of Seven (G-7) most industrialized nations
honors an agreement signed between the two sides in 1995 that G-7
would fund two new nuclear power stations in return for Ukraine's
shutdown of the Chernobyl power plant.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine will continue to use the nuclear power plant on the
basis of reliability and safety because it is cheaper, Kuchma said.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder said that the German government will make a decision
by September on whether to join the multinational program to aid
Ukraine in funding the two new nuclear power stations.
</P>
<P>
The G7 -- which groups the United States, Germany, Japan,
Britain, France, Italy and Canada -- agreed to hold off a decision
on going ahead with the new reactors until after Schroeder had
visited Ukraine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
