<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Lifts Ban Conditionally on Sealed European Imports (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China has decided to lift the ban
on imports suspected of being contaminated by the cancer-causing
agent dioxin from four European countries under certain conditions,
according to a latest circular issued by seven government
departments.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made following the latest development of the
investigation and examination by the European Commission and its
relevant members as well as in other nations that have imported
relevant products from Germany, France, the Netherlands and
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Exporters from Germany, France, and the Netherlands need to
produce one of the following documents to have their sealed
exports in China taken off the restricted list, according to the
circular which was jointly issued on July 2 by the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), the Ministry of
Health, the General Administration of Customs, the State
Environmental Protection Administration, the State Administration
for Entry-Exit Inspection and Quarantine, the State Administration
of Internal Trade, and the State Administration for Industry and
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
1. Official documents showing the amount of dioxin contained in
the relevant product or showing the relevant product is dioxin
free, signed by an authoritative examination body authorized by
the host government;
</P>
<P>
2. Government certified document allowing the sales of the
suspected product in its own country after June 1;
</P>
<P>
3. Documents of relevant organizations within the EU certifying
that the suspected product is allowed to be marketed in EU member
nations.
</P>
<P>
The circular said that exporters of suspected products sealed
for storage in China's market can apply for approval from the
Ministry of Health with the above mentioned documents that are
confirmed by the relevant embassy in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Lifts Ban Conditionally on Sealed European Imports (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Those whose products were sealed in Chinese Customs, except for
those banned by Chinese quarantine law, can apply to the State
Administration for Entry-Exit Inspection and Quarantine with the
documents for examination, and then for release approval at the
Ministry of Health.
</P>
<P>
Sealed products that were produced before January 15, 1999 in
Germany, France, the Netherlands and Belgium, have had
restrictions lifted.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the circular has further laid down the scope of
products which will receive an import suspension. They include:
oxen, pigs, birds, rabbits and fish. Other banned products include
fodder (additives excluded), and meat products, eggs and egg
products, milk and milk products, and other products made with
these materials.
</P>
<P>
But sealed suspected products from Belgium will be treated
differently. Belgium exporters will have to show official dioxin-
free documents signed by the European Commission's authorized
examination agencies, and the documents must be confirmed by the
EU mission in China, before the confinement of their products is
lifted.
</P>
<P>
Unless banned by China's quarantine law, animals from Germany,
France and the Netherlands can be exported to China with
certification signed by the relevant administrative departments of
the respective governments stressing that the animals have not
been fed with dioxin-contaminated food. But the time for a
resumption of relevant imports from Belgium is yet to be decided.
</P>
<P>
On June 11, the seven departments issued an emergency circular,
calling for the suspension of the importing of livestock, poultry,
fish, fodder, meat, eggs and dairy products from those countries
as of the day. All the contaminated food brought in by travelers
or mailed from those countries will be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The animals and food that have arrived in China from those
countries will be put in sealed storage and sales suspended, the
circular noted, adding that only those products that pass rigorous
examination will be allowed on sale. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
