<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Approves 50 Firms as Overseas Processing Ventures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Fifty Chinese firms that have
investments abroad have been officially certified and approved as
overseas processing ventures, which gives them priority in terms
of seeking financing, tax returns and future investments hopefully
enabling them to expand their exports volume.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time that overseas Chinese processing firms
have been certified. The 50 firms, based in Africa, Latin America,
Asia and east Europe, mostly started their operations in 1995 and
1996. They have helped the exports of China-made raw materials,
parts and semi-finished goods up to the value of 135 million US
dollars, an official of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation (MOFTEC) told Xinhua Friday.
</P>
<P>
These ventures are now manufacturing motor vehicles,
refrigerators, washing machines and air conditioners in the
overseas areas. The total investment of the Chinese side added up
to 40 million US dollars, according to the MOFTEC official, who
declined to be identified.
</P>
<P>
"Following the certification, they will enjoy preferential
treatment in financing, tax, insurance and applications for the
rights to import and export," said the official. "They therefore
will enjoy a better policy environment for their overseas
operations."
</P>
<P>
To encourage qualified enterprises to invest abroad is a "
strategic measure" to cultivate new growth areas of China's
exports, MOFTEC Minister Shi Guangsheng said earlier this year. A
number of policies have been introduced this year as an
encouragement.
</P>
<P>
The "strategic measure" will benefit both Chinese firms and the
target investment areas, Chinese trade experts said.
</P>
<P>
"While Chinese companies can benefit from the investment, they
also create job opportunities, raise the technical level and meet
the market demand in the target areas," said Sun Weiyan, a
professor with the University of International Business and
Economics in Beijing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
