<HEADLINE> EU Announces New 20-Member Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission's
president designate, Romano Prodi, announced here Friday his new
team, appointing Spain's Pedro Solbes as the key monetary affairs
commissioner responsible for the euro.
</P>
<P>
Sir Leon Brittan, the outgoing commission's vice president for
trade affairs, has been replaced by France's Pascal Lamy. Italy's
Mario Monti was appointed to the post for competition affairs.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Neil Kinnock, outgoing transport commissioner, was
named the new European Union (EU) executive's vice president in
charge of EU reform.
</P>
<P>
Austria's Franz Fischler, one of four holdovers from the 20-
member outgoing Commission, remains in charge of agricultural
affairs.
</P>
<P>
Prodi was agreed by the leaders of 15 EU member states to
reform the EU executive arm after it resigned en masse on March 15,
following the exposure of fraud and corruption probed by an
independent body. 
