<HEADLINE> Trial of Cambodian Human Rights Workers Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A Cambodian court Friday
suspended the trial of two Cambodian human rights workers on
charges of involvement in illegal demonstrations and inciting
violence.
</P>
<P>
The court's judge Try Lay An said the trial will resume on July
21. The reason he gave for the suspension of the trial was that
more witnesses are needed and lawyers are busy.
</P>
<P>
The trial of Meas Minear, 30, and Kim Sen, 37, began on
Thursday in the southwestern city of Sihanoukville. They were
charged with involvement in illegal demonstrations and incitement
leading to violence and property damage during violent protests
last December prompted by the dumping of toxic wastes by a Taiwan
company in Sihanoukville.
</P>
<P>
Protesters, enraged by the danger of the wastes, destroyed the
building of the goods-inspection office and looted the villa of
the city's deputy governor.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that at least four died and 18 were injured in
the protests and road accidents as residents fled the town.
</P>
<P>
During the trial, the two insisted they were not involved in
any illegal activities, but only monitoring the demonstrations and
providing legal advice to the protesters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
