<HEADLINE> EU Proclaims List of New EU Executives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU)'s new
executive arm was officially formed on Friday following the
announcement of its 19 prospective members of portfolios by
European Commission president designate Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
The following is the list of the new European Commission team
members and posts:
</P>
<P>
1. President: Romano Prodi
</P>
<P>
2. Vice-president for administrative reform: Meil Kinnock
</P>
<P>
3. Vice-president for relations with the European Parliament,
</P>
<P>
Transport and Energy: Loyola de Palacio
</P>
<P>
4. Commissioner for Competition: Mario Monti
</P>
<P>
5. Commissioner for Agriculture and Fisheries: Franz Fischler
</P>
<P>
6. Commissioner for Enterprise and Information Society: Erkki
Liikanen
</P>
<P>
7. Commissioner for the Internal Market: Frits Bolkestein
</P>
<P>
8. Commissioner for Research: Philippe Busquin
</P>
<P>
9. Commissioner for Economic and Monetary Affairs: Pedro
Solbes Mira
</P>
<P>
10. Commissioner for Development and Humanitarian Aid: Poul
Nielson
</P>
<P>
11. Commissioner for Enlargement: Gunter Veriieugen
</P>
<P>
12. Commissioner for External Relations: Christopher Patten
</P>
<P>
13. Commissioner for Trade: Pascal Lamy
</P>
<P>
14. Commissioner for Health and Consumer Protection: David
Byrne
</P>
<P>
15. Commissioner for Regional Policy: Michel Barnier
</P>
<P>
16. Commissioner for Education and Culture: Viviane Reding
</P>
<P>
17. Commissioner for Budget: Michaele Sciireyer
</P>
<P>
18. Commissioner for Environment: Margot Wallstrom
</P>
<P>
19. Commissioner for Justice and Home Affairs: Antonio Vitorino
</P>
<P>
20. Commissioner for Employment and Social Affairs: Anna
Diamantopoulou
</P>
<P>
Under the Treaty of Amsterdam, the EU's basic law, the 19
designated Commissioners have for the first time been agreed upon
between the governments of the 15 EU member states and the
incoming president. But the choice of prospective Commissioners
announced Friday must be approved by the European Parliament
before the appointments are made official by the 15 governments.
</P>
