<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albanian Foreign Minister in Greece for Talks on Deportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal
Milo arrived here Friday for talks with Greek officials on the
deportation by Greece of illegal Albanian immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after his talks with Greek Parliament President
Apostolos Kaklamanis, Milo said that they jointly ascertained that
passing phenomena should not have repercussions on the "very good
relations" between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Kaklamanis stressed the need for further
cooperation between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to tackle the problem and restore the climate that
has existed in Greek-Albanian relations and reflects the desire of
the two peoples to live peacefully," he said.
</P>
<P>
Greece has since last Friday begun a nationwide crackdown on
illegal immigrants, mostly Albanians, in a bid to fight increasing
crimes and provide a clear picture of how many foreigners were
living legally in the country.
</P>
<P>
Currently, there are an estimated 700,000 illegal immigrants in
Greece. According to the deadline set by the Greek government,
all illegal immigrants should have applied for a green card to
work before June 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Greece's Labor and Social Security Minister Miltiadis
Papaioannou warned earlier this week that some 500,000 illegal
immigrants who have not applied for a green card or have entered
the country illegally since the deadline for submissions would
face deportation.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Greece has since the beginning of the year started to
deport illegal immigrants. Some 50,000 illegal immigrants, mostly
Albanians, have been ordered to leave Greece.
</P>
<P>
Dissatisfied with the deportation by Greece of large numbers of
Albanians, Tirana has sought explanations from Athens for its
deportation operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
