<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Advance ASEAN Tariff Schedule by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will have 9,100
tariff lines in the inclusion list in the year 2000, ahead of the
full implementation of the ASEAN Free Trade Area in 2003.
</P>
<P>
The lines represent almost 90 percent of Malaysia's total
tariff lines at 0-5 percent tariff in the year 2000, said Minister
of International Trade and Industries Datuk Seri Rafidah Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Of the 9,100 tariff lines, she said, 4,850 are with zero
percent tariff, 2,953 with tariffs ranging from 1-5 percent, 70
ranging from 6-10 percent and 1,227 ranging from 11-20 percent,
including 408 tariff lines on specific duty rates.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah was speaking at a seminar on "Business Opportunities In
Malaysia" in Tokyo, Japan, and the text of the speech was released
here Friday.
</P>
<P>
As at April, 1999, 85.4 percent or 47,489 of the total ASEAN
tariff lines are in the inclusion list, of which 73 percent have
duties ranging from 0-5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Individually, she said, all countries of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will have at least 85 percent of
their tariff lines at 0-5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The current average regional tariff is 4.5 percent and it is
expected to be 3.7 percent by next year.
</P>
<P>
Against this backdrop, Rafidah invites Japanese investors to
explore further investment opportunities in Malaysia because they
will enjoy the benefits of an expanded market in the ASEAN where
tariffs will be 0-5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
"The Malaysian government offers attractive incentives for
various promoted products and activities such as high-tech
industries, research and development and skills training," she
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Three Emphases" Education Drive to Boost Anti-Corruption Campaign: Wei Jianxing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The current education drive
underlining "Three Emphases," theoretical study, political
awareness and good conduct, is aimed at improving the quality of
officials and bolstering the nationwide anti-corruption drive.
</P>
<P>
Wei Jianxing, a member of the Standing Committee of the
Political Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party (CPC) Central
Committee, made these comments at a meeting to inaugurate the
education drive in the Central Commission for Discipline
Inspection of the CPC and Ministry of Supervision.
</P>
<P>
Wei termed the education as a creative exploration of the
Communist Party of China (CPC) and urged leading officials in the
discipline inspection and supervision departments to deeply
understand the inevitability, urgency and significance of the
education.
</P>
<P>
"Further progress has been made in the country's anti-
corruption battle, but corruptive elements are still breeding in
some localities and units," he said. "Some problems are very
serious," he added.
</P>
<P>
He proposed that the "Three Emphases" education drive can be
taken as a turning-point to ceaselessly explore the
characteristics and law of and effective approaches for improving
the Party's work style, building a clean government and fighting
corruption under the condition of a socialist market economy and
to increase the foresight and initiative in the anti-corruption
drive.
</P>
<P>
"This anti-corruption drive must be led by the CPC and focused
on the economic development, the central task," he said, adding
that the campaign is a long-term one.
</P>
<P>
He noted that officials from discipline inspection and
supervision departments are at the forefront of the anti-
corruption drive and should play an exemplary role in abiding by
the Party's political and work discipline.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Avoids Comment on Pak Appeal to Kashmir Militia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman of the Indian
External Affairs Ministry Friday refused to comment on a decision
of the Pakistani government of "appealing to the Mujahideen
(freedom fighters) to help resolve the current situation in
Kargil" of Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Committee of the Cabinet, the highest
decision-making body on national defense and security in Pakistan,
in its meeting Friday decided to "appeal to the Mujahideen to help
resolve the Kargil situation."
</P>
<P>
The Indian spokesman said his country has maintained that there
were no tangible signs on the ground of withdrawal of Pakistani
troops and mercenaries since the signing of the joint statement
between U.S. President Bill Clinton and Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif in Washington last Sunday, in which Pakistan pledged
to persuade the Mujahideen to withdraw.
</P>
<P>
India has stuck to its firm position that its military
operations would continue in full force till all the "intruders"
are driven out of the Indian side of the Line of Control in
Kashmir, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
