<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ITF to Experiment Larger, Slower Balls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The International Tennis
Federation has voted to experiment with three different types of
balls depending on the surface to slow down the men's game.
</P>
<P>
According to the decision taken at the 1999 AGM, a slow pace
ball, eight percent larger than standard, will be used on fast
surfaces such as grass or indoor carpet.
</P>
<P>
A faster, harder and lower-bouncing ball will be used on slow
surfaces such as clay with the existing ball will be used on
medium-paced surfaces.
</P>
<P>
The tennis ruling body hailed the experimental introduction of
balls as "a great step forward", thinking it will make the men's
competition "more attractive to spectators".
</P>
<P>
Critics have claimed that the 240 kph service speeds in the men
's game have reduced the sport to a contest of strength and that
the skill and artistry of the game have disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The two-year experiment will begin in January 2000 and be
conducted from club level to the lower reaches of the Davis and
Fed Cups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arctic Expedition Ship Fixes Oil Leak Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A potentially dangerous oil
leak on China's North Pole Expedition ship the Snow Dragon was
repaired after six hours today.
</P>
<P>
Lubricating oil was found to be leaking out of the ship's main
engine as it sailed through the treacherous Bering Sea this
morning. The ship immediately weighed anchored at 55.54 north
latitude and 164.37 east longitude for emergency repairs.
</P>
<P>
"The oil was leaking at a loss of one to two tons a day. If the
cause was not found quickly the safety of the ship would have been
endangered," said Xu Jianshe, a technician.
</P>
<P>
After successful repairs this afternoon the Snow Dragon
continued its journey to the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Shaohong, the captain, said the pause did not affect the
future timetable and he expects to reach the harbor of Nome in the
United States on July 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
