<HEADLINE> Chinese, Kazakh Entrepreneurs Discussing Ways for Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Kazakh government has mapped
out a long-term development plan for trade and economic
cooperation with China and has presented it to the Chinese
government for study, according to visiting Kazakh Deputy Prime
Minister and Foreign Minister Kasymzhomart Tokayev.
</P>
<P>
At a China-Kazakhstan trade seminar which opened here today,
Tokayev said the new plan focuses on promoting cooperation between
local areas of the two countries, setting up joint ventures in
various forms, and increasing exchanges of production experience
and advanced technology in many areas including industry, machine
building, transportation, telecommunications, agriculture,
textiles, pharmaceuticals and medical equipment.
</P>
<P>
In order to establish direct contacts with Chinese enterprises,
he said, some 30 Kazakh companies sent representatives to join his
delegation, and this is expected to help expand cooperation on the
basis of mutual benefits.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiang, vice-minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation, said at the opening ceremony that the increased
exchanges and cooperation between governments and entrepreneurs of
the two countries in recent years have promoted the development of
the Sino-Kazakh economic and trade cooperation both in scale and
level.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the total trade volume between
China and Kazakhstan amounted to 375 million U.S. dollars in the
first five months this year, more than double that a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
So far, some 370 Chinese enterprises have set up joint ventures
in Kazakhstan, involving a total investment of 330 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that there still exist great potentials in bilateral
economic and trade cooperation. He hoped that the seminar will
help Chinese and Kazakh entrepreneurs to better understand the
products and market demand of the two countries for further
cooperation in the next century.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 entrepreneurs from the two countries attended
today's seminar.  
</P>
</TEXT>
