<HEADLINE> Li Peng Meets Japanese PM (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, chairman of the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee, said here
today that the NPC is very much in favor of the growth of Sino-
Japanese relations and is ready to reinforce its friendly contact
with Japanese parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
Li made the statement during a meeting with visiting Japanese
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi here this afternoon. He said that the
NPC is willing to make joint efforts with the Japanese parliament
to advance Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said that Japan is also ready to boost the exchange
between the parliamentarians of the two countries and hopes that
more deputies to the NPC would visit Japan.
</P>
<P>
Li elaborated his ideas on economic globalization and world
multi-polarization. He said that the former is the development
trend of the world economy and the development of the information
industry has made closer the economic links among countries, which
has brought about opportunities for economic growth in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
"China and Japan have substantially reached consensus on the
issue of China's WTO membership, which indicates that Japan favors
China's access into the process of economic globalization," Li
noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Li Peng Meets Japanese PM (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, Li said, the Asian financial crisis which broke out in
1997 has demonstrated that the developing nations are at a
disadvantageous position when it comes to economic globalization
and it is imperative for them to learn to better protect their
legitimate rights.
</P>
<P>
"A multi-polarized world is better than one with a single-
polarity in which one country dominates world affairs," Li
continued, saying that the world itself is diversified and it is
impossible to ask all nations to develop along similar lines. "The
development path of a country could only be decided by the people
of that country," he added.
</P>
<P>
"China does not subscribe to the view that 'human rights
outweigh the sovereignty', because this will provide the pretext
and basis for aggression and interference into the internal
affairs of other countries," Li told Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
China appreciates the fact that Japan has reiterated many times
that it would stick to the path of peaceful development, Li went
on.
</P>
<P>
"China carries out an independent foreign policy of peace and
will continue to contribute to the regional and world peace and
stability," Li noted, adding that the United Nations should
continue to play a positive role in maintaining the world's
security and peace.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said he agrees with Li's viewpoints. He noted that
globalization should be more beneficial to everyone and side
effects should be avoided. "Each nation has its own conditions and
its own way of doing things and it is not in an ideal situation if
one country dominates the world," Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also exchanged ideas on international and
regional issues of common interest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
