<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Denies Deal Involving Marcos Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government denied
Friday that it would allow the use of a portion of the alleged
ill-gotten money of the heirs of the late President Ferdinand
Marcos as collateral for a loan.
</P>
<P>
Reports claimed that the government is wrapping up an agreement
with a New York-based securities firm that allows the government
to borrow from the 590-million-U.S. dollar Marcos funds held in
escrow.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Edgardo Espiritu of the Department of Finance said
such a deal, even if it existed and got the approval of former
First Lady Imelda Marcos as reports claim, has to get the approval
first of all signatories to the escrow account.
</P>
<P>
He said any deal involving the escrow funds should have the
approval of Philippine President Joseph Estrada and the concerned
government agencies, as well as the signatories of the Marcos
foundations in which the accounts were placed.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu said he had merely asked the Philippine National Bank,
where the funds are held in escrow, to determine how the
government can make use of the funds for the benefit of the people
while awaiting the final court decision on the matter.
</P>
<P>
About 150 million of the 590 million dollars of the escrow
accounts would be set aside by the government to compensate
victims of human rights abuses law during the Marcos
administration, following an agreement reached by the victims with
the Marcoses.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Estrada said he wants an early resolution to
cases involving the wealth of the Marcoses so that the government
can use the money to bankroll government programs to improve the
life of the poor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
