<HEADLINE> Delegates Seeking World Women's Youth Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Delegates at a Women's Football
Symposium was seeking a world women's youth championship
comparable to FIFA's under-20 or under-17 World Cups for boys,
according to reports on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Reports said a 10 percent increase in women playing in national
federation-sanctioned events over the next four years and
promoting women within the decision-making levels also were set as
goals for the international soccer community in the symposium's "
Los Angeles Declaration on Womens' Football."
</P>
<P>
The two-day symposium, which concluded on Thursday, was held in
conjunction with the weeklong preparations for the Women's World
Cup final on Saturday between China and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We're putting this on the hands of the national associations
and confederations," Per Ravn Omdal of Norway, chairman of FIFA's
Committee for Women's' Football, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Omdal said a next step would be for FIFA, as part of its
distribution of profits from the 2002 World Cup to the national
associations and regional confederations, to require those bodies
use a fixed percentage of the money to develop the women's game.
</P>
<P>
Despite only 63 of FIFA's 203 registered federations taking
part in qualifying for the 1999 Women's World Cup, Omdal said he
is confident many nations would participate in a world youth
qualifying tournament if FIFA sanctioned such an event. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
