<HEADLINE> Keizo Obuchi Boosts Sino-Japanese Cooperation in Environmental Protection (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Japanese Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi planted five pine trees in the Oriental Cherry Yard
in Yuyuantan Park this afternoon, helped by nearly 100 Chinese and
Japanese children.
</P>
<P>
As his two predecessors have made efforts to boost
environmental cooperation between Japan and China, he would like
to do something as well, like tree-planting, Obuchi had said prior
to his China tour, referring to the efforts as "a trilogy of Sino-
Japanese cooperation in environmental protection."
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, former Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita
advocated developing Japan-China environmental protection schemes.
Several years after that, Ryutaro Hashimoto mapped out cooperative
projects in environmental protection between some pilot cities in
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Oriental Cherry Yard is the largest specialized garden in
north China, where over 3,000 oriental cherry trees blossom in
Spring, attracting a great number of tourists.
</P>
<P>
Today students from a primary school in the vicinity, as well
as Japanese children from two Japanese schools in Beijing and
Yianjin gathered here to plant pine trees.
</P>
</TEXT>
