<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's External Trade Decreases in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The value of re-exports of Hong
Kong decreased by 2.3 percent over a year earlier to 94.8 billion
HK dollars (12.2 billion U.S. dollars) and that of domestic
exports went down by 15 percent to 13.8 billion HK dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the value of imports fell by 12.5 percent to 108.9
billion HK dollars, according to the Census and Statistics
Department Friday.
</P>
<P>
Comparing May 1999 with May 1998, a marked increase was
recorded in the value of re-exports to the Republic of Korea, by
56.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Increases were also registered in the value of re-exports to
Singapore, France, the United States, Taiwan, Britain and Japan.
</P>
<P>
However, decreases were recorded in the value of re-exports to
the Netherlands, the Chinese mainland and Germany.
</P>
<P>
Reflecting the on-going structural shift from domestic exports
to re-exports, the value of domestic exports to most of the main
destinations showed decreases of various magnitudes.
</P>
<P>
The value of domestic exports to Singapore, Taiwan and Japan
fell by 39.5 percent, 26.7 percent and 23.8 percent in May 1998
over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the value of imports from most of the major suppliers
showed decreases of various magnitudes, from May 1998.
</P>
<P>
The value of imports from the United States dropped by 30.5
percent, the Republic of Korea by 27.4 percent and Germany by 25.6
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
