<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Students Protest Against New Press Law, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- About 200 Iranian university
students staged a rally here Thursday night to protest against the
newly-approved press law and a ban on the popular moderate daily
Salam (Hello), a spokesman from the Interior Ministry announced
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Bahaeddin Sheikholeslam, said that the students
shouted slogans outside the Tehran University dormitory, marched
toward the freeway nearby and scuffled with plainclothes
policemen.
</P>
<P>
He said that a number of students and police officers were
injured in the scuffle and were transferred to nearby hospitals,
the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Sheikholeslam said that the policemen entered the scene of the
protest without informing the Interior Ministry and arrested a
number of the students at the dormitory.
</P>
<P>
After the incident, the security council of Tehran province
convened and decided to release all arrested students except the
organizers of the rally, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian conservative-dominated Majlis (parliament) on
Wednesday approved the general outlines of a new press law,
threatening to put more strict rules and pressure on the country's
freedom-seeking press.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the country's most popular moderate daily
Salam was closed down by the conservative-dominated judiciary for
publishing a "classified document" of the Intelligence Ministry.
</P>
<P>
However, the Intelligence Ministry announced later to drop its
complaint against Salam in order to "prevent tension in the
country."
</P>
<P>
Salam reported Tuesday in its front page that Saeed Emami, one
of the main agents behind serial political killings in the
country, had proposed to amend the country's press law in order to
control the press.
</P>
<P>
It said that Emami, former deputy intelligence minister for
security affairs, sent a letter last October to the then
intelligence minister, calling on the ministry to raise proposals
to amend the press law.
</P>
<P>
Emami, well-known as Islami, was arrested for masterminding
killings of several Iranian dissidents and committed suicide in
prison on June 19 by taking depilatory substance while taking a
bath.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Iran Nation Party Darius Forouhar and his wife
were stabbed to death at home while at least three dissident
writers were mysteriously killed in Tehran later last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
