<HEADLINE> HK Government Final Accounts Show Lower Expenditure, Higher Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The final accounts of the Hong
Kong Special Administration Region Government for the financial
year 1998-99 ending March 31, 1999 show that government
expenditure was lower and revenue higher than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
According to the figures published Friday in the government
Gazette, expenditure for the year amounted to 239.3 billion HK
dollars (30.67 billion U.S. dollars) and revenue to 216.1 billion
HK dollars (27.70 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The resultant deficit for the year amounted to 23.2 billion HK
dollars (2.97 billion U.S. dollars), which is 9.1 billion HK
dollars (1.16 billion U.S. dollars) lower than the revised
estimate of 32.3 billion HK dollars (4.14 billion U.S. dollars)
announced by Financial Secretary Donald Tsang Yam-kuen in his
budget speech in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
Revenue was 3.3 billion HK dollars (423 million U.S. dollars)
higher and expenditure 5.8 billion HK dollars (743.5 million U.S.
dollars) lower than anticipated at the time of the revised
estimate.
</P>
<P>
"The additional revenue was attributable to higher than
anticipated earnings on the investment of the fiscal reserves with
the Exchange Fund," a government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The lower than forecast expenditure comprised lower than
expected recurrent spending of 2.6 billion HK dollars (333.3
million U.S. dollars) spread over a wide range of items, and lower
capital spending of 3.2 billion HK dollars (410.2 million U.S.
dollars) arising largely from delays in the acquisition of a
number of major capital items together with a lower than expected
take-up from a number of loan assistance schemes," the spokesman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
