<HEADLINE> OAU Ministerial Session to Discuss Ethio-Eritrean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The border conflict between
Ethiopia and Eritrea will be discussed Friday, the second day of
the ministerial meeting of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
here in the Algerian capital.
</P>
<P>
The eruption of the conflict between the two Horn of African
countries, which came as a most unexpected development to the
continental bloc and the international community at large, was one
of the major concerns of the annual OAU ministerial and summit
meetings last year.
</P>
<P>
OAU has been making sustained efforts at the level of
ambassadors, ministers and heads of state in bringing the
conflicts to a peaceful end.
</P>
<P>
A proposal, known as OAU framework agreement, was made on
November 8, 1998 to press for an immediate cessation of
hostilities, redeployment of the armed forces present in Badme,
one of the disputed areas along the common border between the two
neighboring countries, and the deployment of a group of military
observers to supervise the redeployment and demilitarization
process for the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Despite all the efforts made, the two sides have been fighting
each other in the border areas, with each side accusing the other
for ignoring the OAU peace framework.
</P>
<P>
The 35th OAU summit, the last of the century, is seen as yet
another chance for peace along the border of the two east African
countries.
</P>
<P>
The three-day ministerial meeting, a preparation for the 35th
summit of OAU, presents a series of document on the making and
preserving of peace in the conflicts-ridden continent for the
forthcoming summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
