<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Calls for Urgent Talks on U.S. Lamb Tariff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Australia Friday urged the
international trade umpire to convene an urgent meeting to try to
overturn a new U.S. tariff on Australian lamb.
</P>
<P>
Australia lodged a formal request in Geneva for World Trade
Organization (WTO) consultations after the United States announced
a three-year tariff and quota program designed to help U.S. lamb
producers compete against Australian and New Zealand imports.
</P>
<P>
Australia's acting Prime Minister and Trade Minister Tim
Fischer said this would trigger a meeting with the U.S. trade
representative, which Australia wants to be held this week.
</P>
<P>
In a later statement, Fischer's office said Australia had
requested consultations in the next week in Washington.
</P>
<P>
However, Fischer ruled out retaliatory action toward the United
States, saying such a move could cost thousands of Australian
jobs.
</P>
<P>
The move came as Australia's state and territory trade
ministers met in Australia's Darwin city and passed a unanimous
resolution condemning the outbreak of protectionism in the United
States on the lamb issue.
</P>
<P>
The resolution condemned "the total lack of justice and
fairness with the decision of the United States to impose barriers
on Australian lamb exports."
</P>
<P>
It also supported the Australian and New Zealand governments'
decision to take action in the WTO.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration decided on Wednesday to impose a
9-percent tariff on Australian lamb and a quota which limits
imports for the next year to the 1998 levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
