<HEADLINE> SilkAir Suspends Services to Jakarta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- SilkAir Friday announced that it
would suspend its 12-time weekly scheduled services to the
Indonesian capital, Jakarta, from July 26, 1999, so as to focus
its attention on flights to other places in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
SilkAir said in a press release that the decision was taken
following a network review conducted in the light of the recent
economic crisis in the region.
</P>
<P>
SilkAir General Manager Mak Swee Wah was quoted as saying,
"Traffic between Singapore and Jakarta has declined over the past
year and the present capacity on the route is more than adequate."
</P>
<P>
"The route is well served by our parent company, Singapore
Airlines, which offers a seven-time weekly service," Mak said.
</P>
<P>
SilkAir also operates flights to eight other destinations in
Indonesia and Mak claimed Indonesia remains a vital part of
SilkAir's network and his company will continue to develop and
promote traffic to these destinations.
</P>
<P>
SilkAir has operated its services to Indonesian destinations
for a long time and its network covers 20 cities overseas.
</P>
