<HEADLINE> Socio-Economic Strategy Tops OAU Priorities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ALGIERS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) member countries are to make
socio-economic strategy for Africa as one of the top priorities at
the on-going session of the continental bloc.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the African Economic Community, a 34-year
program which started in 1991, will be one of the hot topics in
the continental socio-economic strategy, as Africa is trying to
find its place in the changing world in the new millennium,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim presented Friday a
report concerning the socio-economic development of the
pan-African organization before the 70th session of the OAU's
Working and Social Affairs Commission being held here.
</P>
<P>
Employment situation in Africa, the development of human
sources in Africa's social economic development, and Africa's
strategy for the fight against drug-trafficking constituted the
main subjects in the report.
</P>
<P>
Employment situation in Africa is still worsening, he said, as
the annual growth of labor, which is at the rate of three percent,
is accompanied by a rate of job creation approaching two to 2. 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of recommendations call particularly on political
and social stability, the development of structural adjustment
programs adapted to the countries' reality, the reduction or the
cancellation of debts, and the protection against the excess of
liberalization of economy.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief also stressed that the effectiveness of training
policies and programs which concern the whole population, should
be guaranteed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
