<HEADLINE> Dutch Likely to Get Tough on Soccer Hooligans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Government officials are
considering tightening anti-hooligan laws ahead of next year's
European soccer championship which is co-hosted by Dutch and
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Under current legislation, soccer fans charged with public
order offences are freed ahead of their trial on condition of good
behaviour.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch cabinet will discuss on Friday a proposal which will
enable judges to lock up even minor offenders if they believe
there is a significant risk of further trouble.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has already approved legislation that would allow
police to hold groups of suspected troublemakers for up to 12
hours. But the bill remains to be approved by parliament. 
