<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Olympic Champion to Return from Injury layoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Triple Olympic champion Marie-Jose
Perec will stage her comeback in Casablanca next week after
injuries have kept her out of top competition for two seasons.
</P>
<P>
The French sprinter announced on Friday at a news conference
that she will run the 400 meters at a track meet on July 15,
adding that after that race she will decide on her programs for
the rest of the track season.
</P>
<P>
Perec, 31, grabbed the 1996 Atlanta Olympics titles in 200
meters and 400 meters. She also came away with the 400-meter gold
medal in 1992 Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
But she has had terrible luck since the 1997 World
Championships in Athens, where she injured a hamstring while
preparing for the 200-meter semifinal race.
</P>
<P>
She had to pull out of the European Championships in Budapest
last year. Soon after, she was diagnosed with mononucleosis and
has not run competitively since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
