<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Great Lakes Reported at Lowest Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Similar reports are coming from Lake Erie about its lowest
water level since 1967. Lakes Michigan and Huron were also at
their lowest points since 1990, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
If this summer's hot temperatures and low rainfall persist, the
daily continued, commercial ships might not be able to navigate
the St. Lawrence Seaway.
</P>
<P>
But the problem is by no means limited to water course
navigation. The Council of Canadians predicts that the country
will be at the center of a global water crisis as foreign
businesses seek to privatize and export Canadian fresh water
abroad.
</P>
<P>
The trouble is being complicated by the fact that at least
three U.S. companies have already sued Canada under the North
America Free Trade Agreement for refusing to allow businesses to
export Canadian water to the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The impacts of low water levels, which can also find their way
to hydro-electric production and big breweries, would be even more
damaging if they stayed a permanent way.
</P>
<P>
More salt water would move in from the ocean, endangering
freshwater supplies for towns on the St. Lawrence River. Marshes
and the plants and animals that live in them could be destroyed.
Contaminated sediments once under water would be exposed, the
daily newspaper warned.
</P>
<P>
Although many insist current water levels are within typical
cycles, others fear the problem is real and imminent: "If you
reduce the rainfall a little and raise the temperatures, it can
have a big effect," an export was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The argument is based on the reality that the Great Lakes have
a large surface area, which means they're prone to high levels of
evaporation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
