<HEADLINE> Employment Considered as Means Against Poverty in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Employment is considered as a real
means of struggle against poverty in Africa, according to
representatives of African trade unions who are attending their
first summit here in Algerian capital.
</P>
<P>
Trade union leaders were unanimous in saying that the solutions
to the problems currently prevailing in Africa, notably those
related to debts, economic integration, the fundamental rights of
workers and employment, are a precondition for the improvement of
Africa's socio-economic situation.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Adevati Sunmonu, secretary-general of the Organization
of African Trade Union Unity, said "there could not be an
eradication of poverty without employment."
</P>
<P>
African continent should draw lessons from past experiences to
face the social injustice and the absence of solidarity of
workers, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Ismail Sehbani, secretary-general of the Tunisian Trade Union,
indicated Thursday on the first day of the union meeting that
Africa must not cut off itself from the rest of the world at the
turn of the century when the world is witnessing an economic
globalization.
</P>
<P>
The two-day African trade union meeting will submit a
declaration of the continent's trade unions for the summit of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) scheduled for Monday to
Wednesday. 
</P>
