<HEADLINE> New Man-made Beach for Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- A 35-hectare swimming area opened
today in the Pudong New Area, the financial and trade zone in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Administrative committee sources say that it is just a part of
the city's efforts to create more favorable living conditions for
tourists, investors, and local people.
</P>
<P>
Because of silt that washes down the Yangtze River into the
East China Sea at the northern part of Shanghai, the beaches along
the city's coastline are all very dirty and impossible to use for
swimming.
</P>
<P>
So, the man-made site was made with a small dam and by
filtering sea water from the eastern end of Pudong. The sand on
the 1,300-meter beach has been hauled in. There are some 100,000
square meters of palm trees and grass, with dozens of huts and
pavilions scattered about.
</P>
<P>
Pudong has a goal of becoming an international finance, trade,
tourism, conference, and exhibition center in the next century. It
was set up in 1990 and has completed 10 major infrastructure
projects, with another 10 under construction. These already there
include an international airport, a subway, and a pedestrian
passage across the Huangpu River, which separates it from downtown
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that investors from more than 60
countries and regions have established 5,437 projects in the area,
worth 28 billion U.S. dollars. The list of investors includes 88
of the world's top 500 multinationals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
