<HEADLINE> Pakistani Leaders Endorse Joint Statement With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's political and military
leadership Friday endorsed the joint statement on the Kargil
crisis in Kashmir signed during the visit by Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif to the United States this week, and appealed to the
Mujahideen (freedom fighters) to help resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
This was the main message came from a meeting of the Defense
Committee of the Cabinet (DCC) presided over by Sharif, who
returned home Thursday from his visit to the United States and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The DCC expressed satisfaction that the Joint Statement issued
in Washington during Sharif's visit to the United States had
included the main elements of Pakistan's position on the Kargil
crisis:
</P>
<P>
-- Respect for the Line of Control in Kashmir by both India and
Pakistan;
</P>
<P>
-- De-escalation of the volatile situation in Kargil and,
subsequently, the resumption of the dialogue for a final
settlement of the Kashmir dispute as part of the Lahore process.
</P>
<P>
The DCC decided that "Pakistan should appeal to the Mujahideen
to help resolve the current Kargil situation and provide an
opportunity to the international community to play an active role
for the realization of the legitimate aspirations of the Kashmiri
people and to promote peace and development in South Asia."
</P>
<P>
The DCC appreciated Sharif's diplomatic initiatives including
the efforts with the G-8 (group of eight) for a better
understanding of Pakistan's position, his visit to China earlier
this month and his contacts with world leaders.
</P>
<P>
The meeting expressed appreciation of U.S. President Bill
Clinton's pledge to continue to take "personal interest" in
encouraging an expeditious resumption and intensification of the
dialogue process between Pakistan and India for resolving all
issues including the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
The DCC considered the pledge a "significant development" as it
was the first time that the United States had agreed to play such
a role in the search for the final settlement of the Kashmir
dispute.
</P>
<P>
Participants in Friday's DCC meeting, the second since the
outbreak of the Kargil crisis in early May, included main cabinet
ministers and the three services chiefs of the Pakistani Army. The
DCC held its first meeting on the crisis on July 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
