<HEADLINE> S. African Rand Weaker on Dollar Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The South African rand opened
the day weaker, touching a worst level of 6.1200 against the U.S.
dollar in early trade.
</P>
<P>
The local currency defied its support level and moved weaker as
off- shore players demanded dollars. The rand was last quoted at
6.0880 per dollar from a previous close of 6.0550 of some offshore
dollar buying.
</P>
<P>
Dealers see the day's technical levels of 6.0800 as resistance
level and 6.1200 as a support level.
</P>
<P>
"Asian trade had seen some dollar buying by a San Francisco
bank which sparked a panic causing the rand to weaken to 6.1200,"
said a dealer.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the dollar remained strong, which increased the
demand to hold the safe currency as the world markets were subdued
throughout the night.
</P>
<P>
Sources said there had been some rand selling from Singapore
which depressed the rand.
</P>
<P>
The morning session had seen some profit taking around the
6.0750 level. Local players coming into the market, however,
helped stabilize the rand around the 6.0800 level.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that with gold holding around the 256/257 dollars
an ounce level, it offered some comfort to the local currency.
Bullion was last quoted at 256.00 dollars per ounce from 257.15
dollars at the New York close.
</P>
<P>
A dealer said the rand had, nevertheless, held its own in the
face of a turbulent gold price, due to windfalls from the Old
Mutual listing being slowly factored into the market.
</P>
<P>
South African life assurer Old Mutual lists on the London Stock
Exchange on July 12. Economists expect the Old Mutual listing to
inject around 5 billion rand (833 million dollars) into net
foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the market is beginning to factor in another
decline in interest rates of about 50 basis points by next Friday.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
