<HEADLINE> Nigeria Suggest New Guildline For ECOMOG </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian government Thursday unfolded
a fresh six-point mandate for the Nigeria dominated West Africa
Peacekeeping Force or ECOMOG operations in Sierra Leone with new
thrusts toward reconstruction,
</P>
<P>
disarmament and integration.
</P>
<P>
The six-point mandate, contained in a briefing by the
president's spokesman reaching here Friday, includes
reconstruction, disarmament, mobilization, integration of the
citizenry, training of the Sierra Leonean Armed Forces, and
provision of security for VIPs in the post-war country.
</P>
<P>
The new agenda emanated from the signing three days ago, of the
Lome Peace Agreement between President Tejan Kabbah and Corporal
Foday Sankoh.
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo returned to Abuja Wednesday from
Togo after two hectic days of negotiations toward the resolution
of the conflict - a move which, according to Okupe, was the
president's fresh diplomatic initiative.
</P>
<P>
The government, Okupe said, will commence a process of gradual
and phased withdrawal of Nigerian troops from Sierra Leone in
line with the stage-by-stage progress of the Lome Peace
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
"This action will be in keeping with the electioneering promise
of President Obasanjo to get Nigerian troops back home as soon as
possible, without jeopardy to the peace process and diplomatic
gains already in place," Okupe said.
</P>
<P>
On the contributions of the Nigerian government to the
resolution of the conflict, Okupe said the President had a
well-focused and dynamic approach to the solution, noting that
the fresh approach opened a new vista to the problem which moved
the talk from the earlier rigid position which had negatively
affected the first peace agreement signed between both parties.
</P>
<P>
According to Okupe, the president has embarked on various
diplomatic shuttles to ensure the success of his diplomatic
initiative.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, even before President Obasanjo was sworn-in, during
his international shuttle, he laid the building blocks for the
Lome Peace Agreement when he visited the affected countries and
consulted widely with the leaders," he said.
</P>
<P>
A week after assumption of office, President Obasanjo had
received President Charles Taylor who was in Abuja on June 26, and
also visited Liberia, Sierra Leone and Togo.
</P>
<P>
The president is also billed to travel to Algiers on Monday for
the opening of the 35th OAU summit.
</P>
<P>
"The president is looking forward to the first opportunity to
meet the largest gathering of African leaders to rub minds on the
numerous problems bedeviling the continent, with a view to
finding lasting solutions to them, " he said.
</P>
<P>
The meetings, he remarked, would go a long way in exploring
ways of moving Africa away from the stagnation, conflicts and
under-development which had hindered meaningful growth at the turn
of the new century.  Endetim

