<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Sues Officials for Disappearance of 16,500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's presidential
commissions of inquiry have filed cases in courts against 425
state officials for the disappearance of about 16,500 people from
1980 to 1990, sources of the Attorney General's Department said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
There are complaints about the disappearance of about 16,500
people during the 1980-90 "period of terror" under the former
government of the United National Party, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
When President Kumaratunga's People's Alliance coalition came
to power in 1994, it promised to correct the human rights abuses
of the previous decade.
</P>
<P>
Three commissions were appointed by the president to inquire
into and report these incidents.
</P>
<P>
Based on the reports of these commissions, a special police
unit conducted further investigations and submitted reports on 825
persons found responsible by the commissions.
</P>
<P>
Of these people, cases have been filed against 425 state
officials, mainly from the security forces and the police.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, a U.N. study said that Sri Lanka has the
second highest number of disappeared people in the world, second
only to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Over 12,000 Sri Lankans have gone missing after being detained
by security forces since 1980, said the study by the United
Nations Working Group on Enforced or Involuntary Disappearances.
</P>
<P>
Most of them are said to be young Tamil men accused of
supporting the Tamil rebels fighting for a homeland in Sri Lanka's
north and east. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0151 </DOCNO>
