<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate Considers Approaching US for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Senate has considered
asking the government to sign military pacts with the United
States and any other west European powers to protect the new
civilian government from being toppled again.
</P>
<P>
The motion sponsored by about 12 senators says that "the
government of the Federal Republic of Nigeria should immediately
commence negotiation and sign a military pact with the United
States of America and any other democratic European nation for the
protection of democracy in Nigeria," the Guardian newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The motion was tabled Thursday "in view of the fact that
democratic governance in Nigeria has been rather unstable and
vulnerable to military incursions; and considering the fact that
there has been eight coups in Nigeria since independence in
1960."
</P>
<P>
In another interesting motion, the upper house of the Nigeria's
top legislature was asked to approve some senators' motions which
wanted the re- naming of all the public facilities named after
late military dictator Gen. Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
The motion was tabled "in view of the fact that public
buildings, roads and institutions were unilaterally named after
the late head of state Gen. Sani Abacha, and that many prominent
Nigerians were either assassinated or incarcerated unjustly by
him," said its sponsors.
</P>
<P>
The motion then suggested that the names of the public
facilities should be renamed after "those innocent Nigerians that
were assassinated during the regime of late Gen. Sani Abacha."
</P>
</TEXT>
