<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair's Fox Ban Pledge Raises Hackles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The issue of blood sports has again
aroused passionate debate in the UK, as pro-hunt campaigners have
criticized a new pledge by British Prime Minister to ban fox-
hunting.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister told BBC One's Question Time program on
Thursday that everything possible was being done to ensure it had
space in the next session of parliament, which is due to begin
this autumn. Failing that, he said, space would be found in the
following session.
</P>
<P>
But the Countryside Alliance, which is committed to resisting a
hunting ban, has said rural areas would be hit hard. A spokesman
on Friday asserted the power of the people would overcome that of
the state, saying that "if time is found for a new fox hunting
bill, expect another noisy fight."
</P>
<P>
It was also revealed that the Scottish Parliament may have to
introduce legislation of its own for a ban to be imposed in
Scotland, according to a BBC report.
</P>
<P>
Douglas Ross, the spokesman for the Countryside Alliance in
Scotland, said: "Hunting has been in Scotland since the 1750s and
it has a secure future."
</P>
<P>
"I think it's the height of arrogance at two minutes to
midnight on the BBC's Question Time to announce a package that
would destroy rural Scotland and dustbin 16,000 jobs," he said.
</P>
<P>
But Mike Baker, a spokesman for the Campaign for the Protection
of the Hunted Animal, which represents the League Against Cruel
Sports, the RSPCA and the International Fund for Animal Welfare,
described Blair's remarks as "great news."
</P>
<P>
"The government has really taken note of what the overwhelming
majority of people in Britain believe is a strong moral imperative
for the government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Blair's comments followed the delivery of a petition, which
called for the banning of hunting with hounds and was signed by 42,
500 people, to the Commons on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, hunt supporters gathered outside Downing Street to
warn that a field-sports ban could hit hundreds of jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
