<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt Policies Passed in Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's parliament passed Friday
the policies and programs presented by the government for the
1999/2000 fiscal year starting mid-July.
</P>
<P>
Though the policies and programs were attacked by the
opposition parties as lacking innovation and fresh approach and a
mere adherence to formality, they got passed in voice vote in the
House of Representatives where the ruling Nepali Congress party
holds a majority of seats.
</P>
<P>
The policies and programs focus on poverty reduction on the
national front and identify a number of priority sectors in this
regard.
</P>
<P>
About 42 percent to 50 percent of the population live below the
poverty line and poverty alleviation has been the primary
objective of the government in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
On the international front, the Nepali government has committed
itself, among others, to making the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) more action- and result-oriented.
</P>
<P>
Nepal is scheduled to host the 11th SAARC summit in November
this year. SAARC groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali Congress government took office on May 31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
