<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC's Kathmandu Summit Should be Milestone: Nepali FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Minister Ram Sharan Mahat
said here Friday that Nepal is making all types of preparations
for the forthcoming summit of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) and the summit should be a very
important milestone.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a face-to-face program organized by the Reporters'
Club of Nepal, Mahat said that preparations are being made
physically and logistically for the 11th SAARC summit scheduled to
be held in Kathmandu in November this year.
</P>
<P>
Various resolutions and priority orders are being prepared with
cooperation from the concerned countries and consultations are
underway with these countries to arrive at a time agreeable to all
parties, he said.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, which groups Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka, was formed in December 1985 to
promote social and economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
On the outstanding Bhutanese refugee issue, Mahat said that "we
want a quick resolution of the issue, our policy will be concrete
result-oriented." He said there is an all-party consensus in Nepal
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees are staying in U.N.-run camps
in eastern Nepal after being forced to flee Bhutan in 1989 and
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and Bhutan had held seven rounds of ministerial talks on
the issue but failed to make any headway.
</P>
<P>
Mahat said that the Kalapani and border demarcation issues
between Nepal and India will be resolved through bilateral
consultations on the basis of historical documents.
</P>
<P>
Kalapani in far-western Nepal has been claimed by both
countries for decades.
</P>
<P>
On Indo-Pakistani clashes over Kashmir, the foreign minister
called for both countries to respect the Line of Control and seek
a peaceful resolution.
</P>
<P>
But he said economic development will be the focus of Nepal's
foreign policies. "The economic diplomacy will be continued," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Nepali missions abroad will be made more active and effective
to achieve the goals, he said.
</P>
<P>
He vowed that the government is fully committed to safeguard
the Nepalese people's interests wherever they work.
</P>
<P>
Mahat took office as Nepal's foreign minister on June 30. This
is his first meeting with the press. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
