<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Labor Federations Meet over Job Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG,July 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's two of the
largest trade union federations held separate meetings here on
Friday to discuss the issue of thousands of job losses in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Congress of South African Trade Unions (CSATU) and the
Federation of Unions of South Africa (FUSA) met separately with
their affiliate unions to draw attention to the unemployment
issue.
</P>
<P>
Cosatu spokesman Mukoni Ratshitanga said the meeting was called
to assess the massive job losses, including those in the country's
insurance and gold mining industries.
</P>
<P>
"Reports indicate that we may still experience more (job
losers)," he said
</P>
<P>
Cosatu hoped to come up with a "consolidated organizational
response" to the job loss threats.
</P>
<P>
This could include mass action, Ratshitanga said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the SA Footplate Staff Association, which is
</P>
<P>
affiliated to FUSA, confirmed that the meeting would focus on
the rail company of Spoornet's new restructuring plan which,
according to labour unions, will involve 27000 retrenchments over
the next three years.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned communications company, Telkom, is expected to
shed 10, 000 jobs over the same period, while 11,700 jobs are
possibly on the line at five gold mines.
</P>
<P>
The SA Transport and Allied Workers Union, which has threatened
rolling mass action from Friday to protest Spoornet's
retrenchments, said the mass action would take the form of
lunchtime pickets.
</P>
<P>
"We start notifying workers today (Friday) and on Monday we
will have a full blown demonstration," the union's Gauteng
chairman Frans Marumo said, adding that a national strike was also
a possibility.
</P>
<P>
But Spoornet managing director Saki Macozoma on Thursday night
warned that rail transport would become less viable and more jobs
would be lost if the unions went ahead with mass action.
</P>
<P>
"If they go on strike on Friday, Spoornet will lose more
customers who will never come back to the railways. This can only
result in more job losses," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Rebound on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to rebound
on Singapore Stock Market Friday as institutions returned to the
market and pushed up prices.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI), that chalked up
Thursday for the first time this week, gained 21.77 points to end
at 2,181.63 points in modest trading, off from the intraday high
of 2,192.30 points.
</P>
<P>
The total volume increased to 921.92 million shares valued at
1,031.81 million Singapore dollars (607.66 million U.S. dollars).
Gainers outnumbered losers by 268 to 77 with 100 counters
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The larger block was the 205.24 million stock parcel by Golden
Ag which was transacted at 0.635 U.S. dollars per share. It was
followed by IPC that had 55.36 million units done. Hotung was the
next with 32.885 million counters traded.
</P>
<P>
Bukit Sem topped the actives list of the day surging up 90
cents to close at 18.50 Singapore dollars. DBS F ran up 70 cents
to finish at 20.50 Singapore dollars. DBS and Jar Mat climbed by
50 cents and ended at 17.80 Singapore dollars and 5.70 U.S.
dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SPH headed the descent of the day incurring a
loss of 30 cents to close at 29.70 Singapore dollars. OUE shed 25
cents to finish at 5.25 Singapore dollars. Auric Pac retreated 23
cents to end at 1.77 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers attributed the day's rise to the support from retailers
and institutions that returned to the market after remaining on
sidelines during much of this week's sell-off.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that late profit-taking eroded gains made
during the day.
</P>
<P>
They expected that the market would follow a similar course
next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
