<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak May Suggest Bypassing Parts of Wye Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 9 (Xinhua) -- In his first visit abroad after
taking office, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak is expected to
present his suggestions for bypassing parts of the Wye accord and
moving directly to the final-status talks between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Barak will meet with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in the
Egyptian coastal city of Alexandria Friday morning. Their talks
are expected to focus on improving bilateral relations and moving
the Middle East peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post quoted a source at the Prime Minister's
Office as saying Barak would suggest during the meeting that
Israel carries out the second phase of redeployment according to
the Wye accord, then passes over the third withdrawal, combining
it with the final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
This would mean that Israel would withdraw within weeks from 5
percent of area C (area under full Israeli control) in the West
Bank, but postpone the next redeployment.
</P>
<P>
The next redeployment consists of a 5 percent withdrawal from C
to B (under joint control of Israel and the Palestinians), as well
as a 1 percent withdrawal from C to A (under full Palestinian
control), and a 7.1 percent withdrawal from B to A at a later date.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptians, who call for a full implementation of Wye, are
expected to dismiss Barak's suggestion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mubarak reportedly plans to urge Barak to
immediately freeze all Jewish settlement building in the occupied
territories.
</P>
<P>
Regarding bilateral relations, the emphasis of the talks
between the two leaders, the source said, would be on developing
ways to increase the commercial ties, especially in the field of
energy.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Barak's office has not released information on the
talking points for the meeting, saying only that it would serve as
a chance for Barak to "familiarize" himself with a key regional
leader and begin building up a relationship built on trust.
</P>
<P>
Following his meetings with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
and Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein next week, Barak is to
leave for the United States next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
On the way home the following week, Barak is scheduled to stop
over in Britain to meet with Prime Minister Tony Blair. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
