<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France's Public Debt Grows in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 9 (Xinhua) -- France's public debt rose by 0.3
percent in 1998 over 1997 to 786.8 billion euros (about 803
billion U.S. dollars), according to an official report published
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The public debt represented 60.3 percent of the country's gross
domestic product (GDP) in the same year, surpassing the limit set
by the European Union's Maastricht Treaty, which asks all
countries in the euro zone to control their public debt under 60
percent of their GDP.
</P>
<P>
The figure was published by the French State Institute of
Statistics and Economics Study (INSEE) in its annual report on
public debt.
</P>
<P>
French Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn said Friday morning that
France must continue to strictly control public spending.
</P>
<P>
The euro remained stable in international markets Friday
morning after the French government's announcement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Plans to Lower Birth Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese government is drawing up a
draft of the national population plan for the period after 2000,
which will focus on ways to lower the birth rate, Vietnam News
Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In her recent interview with Vietnam News Agency on the
occasion of the World Population Day (July 11), Nguyen Thi Than,
chairwoman of Vietnam's National Assembly's Committee for Social
Affairs, said the draft was expected to be completed late this
year.
</P>
<P>
She said that over the past five years the allocated spending
for population and family planning programs had increased tenfold.
</P>
<P>
The success of Vietnam's population policies in the last few
years had helped lower population pressure on many areas. "Just
imagine how many more classrooms and jobs we would have to set up
should the population now be 82 million or 83 million rather than
the 77 million it actually is," Than said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam was one of the two countries which have received a
population award from the United Nations this year.
</P>
<P>
The national population growth rate, Than said, had dropped to
2.13 percent in general but the birth rate was still high in some
areas, especially in remote and mountainous regions.
</P>
<P>
In the Red River Delta provinces, the birth rate has fallen
below the fertility level of 1.99 children per woman since 1997.
However, the figure now stood as high as four in the Central
Highlands area and 2.6 to three in most of the central provinces.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnam's national population plan would also contain steps
to address the increasing proportion of the old people, and the
rising migration to urban areas, as well as to combat and prevent
HIV/AIDS, she said.
</P>
<P>
Predicting Vietnam's population growth over the next few
decades, Than said Vietnamese population would be aging, but not
as fast as the global average. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
