<HEADLINE> Uganda Acts Against Drought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
earmarked funds for emergency measures to fight drought and
protect the affected people.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Apolo Nsibambi said many parts of Uganda had been
afflicted by drought and face acute food shortage. People, crops
and animals were endangered, the New Vision newspaper reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Nsibambi said his government had taken emergency steps which
include buying of cattles from badly hit areas. The cattle will be
used for restocking for other districts.
</P>
<P>
''The government also plans to purchase and distribute relief
food to the affected, construct valley tanks, sink bore holes and
desilt dams in the cattle corridor,'' added the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, many parts of the country has not
received reliable rainfall since last November. In southern
Uganda's Mbarara district, 700,000 people are faced with possible
starvation. Farmers in Kabale district in the southwest end of
the east African country expect to harvest less than 40 percent of
the normal sorghum harvest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
