<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Price Controls Suggested to Increase Domestic Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- In a bid to stimulate domestic
demand, China needs to end or reduce some levies on both
individuals and enterprises, the State Development Planning
Commission (SDPC) says.
</P>
<P>
The SDPC was quoted by Friday's Shanghai Securities News as
having asked local governments to use prices to increase domestic
demand and promote growth in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural production could be improved by raising the
purchasing prices of certain farm produce while reducing those of
poor quality products, the commission says in a recent circular.
</P>
<P>
Fees for education, medical care, marriage registration, family
planning, house building, electricity supply, and telephone
services in rural areas should be checked and improved to ease the
burden on farmers, while in urban areas, fees for electricity and
water supply and public transportation should be adjusted to the
ability of urbanites and companies to pay.
</P>
<P>
The SDPC has also asked for better charges for real estate and
has recommended favorable policies to encourage the development of
affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
There will also be strict rules on highway tolls and foreign
investment and public capital will be encouraged in the
construction of roads.
</P>
<P>
Service charges for restructuring enterprises, and registration,
training, management and job hunting fees for the re-employment of
laid-off workers should be reduced or canceled, the SDPC says.
</P>
<P>
Import and export fees will also be lowered to help exporters,
while the dumping of goods will be banned to create a more
favorable environment for state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To increase car sales, the country needs to take a look at fees
for automobile purchase, registration and daily use, it says.
</P>
<P>
The tourism sector, which is also plagued by unreasonable
charges, will be straightened out to make China more attractive to
tourists.
</P>
<P>
And there will be stricter checks on these areas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
