<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Market Analyst Predicts Better Consumer Goods Sales In Latter Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China's consumer goods sales will
be more vigourous in the latter half of the year, according to Guo
Shouzhong, of the State Administration of Internal Trade's
Information Center.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the government's attempts to stimulate the
market will give it a boost in the rest of the year and that buyer
sentiment will gradually increase and reach a peak in the fourth
quarter, the second peak after the Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, however, that annual growth in the consumer
goods market will stay at around 6.6 percent this year, slightly
lower than last year's percentage and this year's 7 percent GDP
growth target.
</P>
<P>
He cited deflation as a major cause of sluggishness in the
market, but said that the state's fiscal measures have, to a
certain degree, increased demand. From January to May, retail
sales were worth more than 1.23 trillion yuan, up 6.6 percent from
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
And, with the over-supply of goods, new areas of activity will
emerge in the second half of the year, Guo said, citing electric
appliances and telecommunications products as examples. These two
categories saw a more than 30-percent growth in sales in the first
two quarters and market demand is still rising.
</P>
<P>
Because of the deepening grain distribution reforms, the price
of some agricultural products and sales have both been rising, he
said, and market demand for livestock products, pork in particular,
will also change for the better, as many farmers sell fewer pigs
and go for in-depth processing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
