<HEADLINE> Dope-Tested Positive, Japanese Cyclist Stripped of Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Japan's top professional cyclist
Yuichiro Kamiyama was stripped of his silver medal won at the
Asian championships last month, after failing to a doping test,
the Japan Cycling Federation announced here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kamiyama's urine sample was found to contain traces of banned
stimulant ephedrine, when being tested by the International
Cycling Union after he finished runner-up in the men's Keirin
final at the Green Dome Maebashi.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old sprint champion from the Bangkok Asian Games
last December was summoned by the Japanese federation Friday. He
explained to the officials that he took the pills in the morning
of the race, mistaking them as vitamins.
</P>
<P>
The federation disqualified his runner-up finish at the Asian
championships and fined him 2,000 Swiss francs (1,300 U.S. dollars)
. He was also suspended for one month till August 9.
</P>
<P>
But Kamiyama, the country's top professional cyclist in the
past two years, however, can compete in domestic professional
races as the Japan Keirin Association decided not to punish him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
