<HEADLINE> Feature: China's Steel Giant Expecting New Life on 50th Birth Anniversary (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANSHAN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Despite its past glories of
providing steel for the country's first China made automobile,
plane and nuclear bomb, the first metallurgical venture of the
Chinese Communist Party embraced its 50th birth anniversary today
without any celebrations.
</P>
<P>
However, celebrations lasted days and nights when the Anshan
Iron and Steel Complex (Angang) turned out its first converter of
steel 50 years ago. "We also held a gala at the city stadium to
celebrate the 30th birth anniversary of the plant," said 83-year-
old Leng Yuelin, a retired worker of Angang.
</P>
<P>
Like many other State enterprises emerged under the planned
economy, this first iron and steel producer of the country in
northeast China's Liaoning province is now mired in difficulties
such as inefficiency, aging equipment, and sales problems. This
year will be vital for Angang to pull out of these problems.
</P>
<P>
A view of the company presents a typical picture of the kingdom
of a Chinese State enterprise: a sprawl of factory buildings
stretching over a hundred square kilometers and a forest of
chimneys, company-run schools, hospitals and even police stations
can also be found in the factory area. The number of workers once
hit 500,000 at its prime time.
</P>
<P>
The huge population of retirees is another woe of the steel
giant, which has to take care of 100,000 such people and help
another 20,000 laid-off workers find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
"All these problems are dealt with by a social security service
in developed countries," the company president Liu Jie said.
</P>
<P>
Today is just not the right time for birthday celebrations, Liu
Jie said. "Angang is facing a problem of survival or death for the
present," he added.
</P>
<P>
In the morning, some workers were posing for pictures before
the No. 2 blast furnace, which produced the first furnace of
melton iron 50 years ago. "We hope to remember the company's past
glories in spite of all the difficulties we are facing today,"
model worker Wang Erjiang told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"China has produced iron for over 2,000 years, and it's Angang
which helped restore the nation's former glory as an iron and
steel giant in the world," Wang said. "In the future, China will
always be in harness with our company," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: China's Steel Giant Expecting New Life on 50th Birth Anniversary (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The company morale also received a good boost when the workers
felt their own destiny are inseparable from the company's and
their welfare depends on the welfare of the company.
</P>
<P>
With his own savings and borrowed money, veteran worker Hu
Kangzhen set up a storehouse to recall idle machine spare parts.
With the help of other workers, Hu has collected more than 3,000
such parts in his storehouse, which may be used to replace failed
parts on other machines.
</P>
<P>
"Cost reduction is vital for the company's competitiveness, as
well as for our incomes," Hu told a team of young workers visiting
his storehouse.
</P>
<P>
But the hope for Angang to restore past glories does not solely
lie in workers' disillusion about life-long employment, nicknamed
as "iron rice bowl" in China, Yang said, Angang is also building a
modern enterprise mechanism to survive market competition.
</P>
<P>
For the present, a lot of subsidiary units of Angang have
become its affiliations independent in management and finance, and
some other subsidiaries unrelated with steel production have also
disengaged from Angang. Schools and hospitals run by the company
are being handed over to the city government. It has also set up
share-holding companies to pool funds through public listing on
stock markets in Hong Kong and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
"We felt strange when we set out to do all these novel things,
but the result is promising: we are already starting to make
profit," company manager Na Jin said. "There is nothing that we
Angang people can not achieve."
</P>
<P>
In one of the factory workshops stands a three-man high open-
hearth furnace, once the biggest in the nation. This black monster-
like furnace had turned out 12 million tons of steel for the
nation, but it is now no longer in service.
</P>
<P>
Not far from the furnace, two workers are operating the
computer-controlled converter, which can produce four or five
times the steel produced by an open-hearth furnace. The old
furnace, as the witness of the ups and downs of Angang, will be
painted and become a site for visitors.
</P>
<P>
In a large scene, Angang plans to complete an unprecedentedly
massive project in technical renovations by the end of this year.
"Angang will gain a new life then when we will become equally
competitive as any other steel ventures at home or abroad,"
company engineer Yu Shujuan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: China's Steel Giant Expecting New Life on 50th Birth Anniversary (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Angang, some 700 km in northeast of Beijing, was first built in
1916, and it then fell under the colonial rule of the Japanese.
But people take July 9, 1949 as its real birthday, when Angang
resumed its production under the leadership of the Chinese
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
Not long after it gained new life, Angang became a major
logistics supplier in the War to Resist U.S. Aggression and Aid
Korea in the early 1950s. The central government has since spared
no effort to build it into the nation's largest iron and steel
complex.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, Angang was ordered to send 50,000 of its backbone
technicians to help establish major iron and steel plants in other
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
China is the leading steel producer in the world today with an
annual output of more than 100 million tons, 700 times the figure
half a century ago. Angang now produces more than 20,000 tons of
steel a daily.
</P>
<P>
But problems also arose as a result of its prestigious status.
"As the largest iron and steel producer of China, Angang had got
used to producing iron and steel on government orders," deputy
secretary of the company's Party Committee Yang Baoxing said, "
Many people could not believe the fact that the State stopped
purchasing and buying its products in 1995," he added.
</P>
<P>
In spite of its reluctance, Angang departed the haven of
planned economy in the end, and became the last state-owned large
iron and steel producer to step into market. "This indicated China
's determination to adhere to socialist market economy," company
official Ma Enqing said.
</P>
<P>
Ma is leaving for Beijing today to market company products. "
There was no need for us to think about market in the past, but
marketing has become a top priority for us nowadays," Ma said.
</P>
<P>
The company even initiated heated discussions among its workers
about the marketability of its products when one of China's
largest automobile manufacturers declared to stop placing orders
for steel products from Angang because of its poor service.
</P>
<P>
Slogans saying "Client is God" are a common scene in Angang
today, and any worker who is seen to cold-shoulder clients will
have to make a self-criticism or may even be fired.
</P>
<P>
"Steel output is no longer our goal. We regard product quality,
work efficiency and service as our top priorities," Yang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
