<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five-Star Hotel Robbed in Lusaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Two armed bandits brandishing AK-47
rifles staged a dramatic robbery Thursday at a five-star hotel in
Zambian capital Lusaka in broad daylight and got away with about
70 million kwacha (about 28,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The gunmen clad in jeans and T-shirts waylaid a cashier who
had just returned from withdrawing the cash for the salaries of
the hotel staff from a bank at about 14:00 hours at the hotel's
entrance, Times of Zambia reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The bandits grabbed the cash box from the cashier before
speeding off in a car.
</P>
<P>
Hotel workers scampered in all directions right afterwards.
</P>
<P>
According to another local newspaper, The Post, police officers
have been placed at all filling stations here with effect from
Thursday to prevent possible robberies because of the expected
huge cash-collections during the critical fuel shortage period.
</P>
<P>
As the petrol shortage is biting the country, the fuel prices
rose by 12. 8 percent from Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Armed robberies have been on the rise in the southern African
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
