<HEADLINE> China, Japan Conclude WTO Talks (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two said that China's accession is in the common interest
of China and Japan and also in the interest of all WTO members.
They agreed to continue their close cooperation in the group talks
in Geneva to reach the goal of China's entry into the WTO as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed the belief that the conclusion of the talks
on China's WTO accession between China and Japan will further
strengthen the bilateral long-term, stable trade and economic
relations.
</P>
<P>
The talks on China's entry into the WTO between China and the
United States came to a standstill following the U.S.-led NATO
attack on the Chinese embassy in Belgrade on May 8.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Trade Minister Shi Guangsheng said earlier that China
hasn't changed its stand, viewpoint, or attitude on its accession
to the WTO. But, he said, now is not the proper time to resume the
WTO talks with either the United States or the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led NATO missile attack on the Chinese embassy in
Belgrade damaged the good negotiation atmosphere, he said, and it
is only when NATO has given a response that China is satisfied
with and the good atmosphere reinstated that the talks can resume.
</P>
