<HEADLINE> Foreign Firms Increase Investment in Hebei Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, July 9 (Xinhua) -- More foreign-funded
enterprises have increased their investment in north China's Hebei
Province after achieving initial good economic returns and thanks
to the province's improving investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics from the provincial foreign investment bureau
show that 11 of the 23 world famous transnational corporations
already in the province, including Siemens, Mitsubishi, Hoechst
and DuPont, have increased their investment and their combined
investment reached 500 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of increased funds was reportedly invested in the iron,
steel, chemicals and electronics sectors.
</P>
<P>
Hebei has approved a total of 5,120 foreign-invested
enterprises with gross investment reaching 7.23 billion dollars
since it began introducing foreign funds in the mid 1980s.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of 1999, the industrial and agricultural
output value of the foreign-funded enterprises in Hebei amounted
to 20.1 billion yuan, up 21 percent on a yearly basis, with the
sales income increasing 25 percent to 22.2 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Hebei approved 50 more foreign-funded enterprises in
the six months, a 24-percent rise over the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the bureau announced that Hebei plans
to use foreign funds to develop its natural gas sector. The
province has a proven reserve of 16 billion cubic meters of oil
and gas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
