<HEADLINE> Germany Offers Mozambique $61.4 Million Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Germany will provide three batches
of assistance totaling 118 million Deutsche marks (about 61.4
million U.S. dollars) to help Mozambique carry out the 1999-2000
development program.
</P>
<P>
This was contained in an agreement signed here Thursday between
Germany and Mozambique after three-day negotiations, the Noticias
newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The major amount of the assistance, about 43.2 million dollars,
will go to agricultural development, employment, basic education,
professional training, medicare, rehabilitation of infrastructure
and de-mining.
</P>
<P>
Another 7.8 million dollars will be used in Caia transformer
substation in central Mozambique's Sofala Province.
</P>
<P>
The rest 104 million dollars is expected for general
merchandise assistance.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on the agreement, the German Embassy in
Mozambique said Germany considers Mozambique as an important
partner in southern Africa. Germany will also help relieve
Mozambique's debt within the framework of the "highly indebted
poor countries initiative".
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is rich in agricultural and forestry resources,
which, according to the statement, will enhance the country's
economic growth through government reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
