<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia Says to Boycott 2002 World Cup Qualifiers (Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Asia said on Thursday it would
boycott the qualifying competition for soccer's 2002 World Cup
because it had not been given enough berths by the world governing
body FIFA, according to reports from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after an emergency meeting of Asian
delegates attending Friday's 203-nation FIFA congress in Los
Angeles said that Asia had no choice but to give up its two
existing qualifying positions and go into the tournament solely
with Japan and South Korea, the joint hosts and automatic
qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
"Since FIFA has not acceded to Asia's request for an extra
qualifying position, it is compelled to boycott the qualifying
tournament," said the statement issued by the Asian Football
Confederation (AFC).
</P>
<P>
"This is a decision of great gravity for world football and for
Mr. (FIFA President Sepp) Blatter, but our members have shown
great solidarity," Malaysian Peter Velappan, AFC's general
secretary, was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"No one should mess about with Asia. All of this has been
totally ignored and (World Cup) seats given away to those who don'
t deserve them," he said.
</P>
<P>
The statement said a full extraordinary meeting of the Asian
congress would take place as soon as possible to endorse the
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
Asia originally wanted a full extra qualifying spot at the
World Cup. Instead, FIFA granted on Tuesday only half a place,
which was given up by European soccer's' governing body UEFA.
</P>
<P>
Asia had earlier raised the boycott threat because of the
matter. And Velappan indicated that Asia might change its mind if
FIFA reconsidered the allocation of berths, the reports said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
