<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Say Int'l Arctic Research Cooperation Needed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China would like to share
research data and the results of its first government-sponsored
North Pole expedition with the world to increase international
cooperation in Arctic Research.
</P>
<P>
Chen Liqi, the chief scientist of Chinese research expedition
said today from aboard the Snow Dragon, which is nearing the
Arctic Ocean, that the study of global environmental changes can
not be done by one country but requires the joint effort of the
whole world.
</P>
<P>
China has joined the International Arctic Science Committee and
would like to make its contribution to Arctic research, said Chen,
who is also in charge of the polar research office of China's
State Oceanic Administration.
</P>
<P>
According to him, first-hand data is very important in
geoscience research but much data on the polar regions has been
kept secret in many countries in the past.
</P>
<P>
But countries have begun to be more open with their data
because of improvements in the international cooperation
atmosphere in recent years and this may produce better results
with less cost, Chen said, pointing to the assistance he and his
team have got from Canada, the United States, and other countries
in this year's research.  
</P>
</TEXT>
