<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Enterprises Paying More Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China's state-owned enterprises
paid 25.3 billion yuan (about three billion U.S. dollars) in
income taxes from January to May, a 38-percent increase over the
same 1998 period, the State Tax Administration reports.
</P>
<P>
Many state enterprises has been losing less money since the
beginning of the year, and their better performance has allowed
them to pay more taxes, according to the administration.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attribute the increase in state revenues to the change
of tax collection from the Finance Ministry to the State
Administration of Taxation last year.
</P>
<P>
They predict that revenues from state enterprise will continue
to grow in the second half of this year, in spite of their other
difficulties, but at a slower pace.  
</P>
</TEXT>
