<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Gov't Considers Food Security Strategies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
considering some food security strategies to do away with
continued dependence on the food import, the Daily Star newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The strategies include keeping the public sector food reserve
at one million tons at the minimum always and providing the
vulnerable section of the rural poor with free food for at least
two months during the lean period of the year when there are
lesser job opportunities in the countryside, official sources were
quoted as stating.
</P>
<P>
The government is not in favor of getting food aid in terms of
cash as is being considered by European donors, they said.
</P>
<P>
As the issue of food security surfaced as a major challenge
amidst mounting pressure on the public exchequer to meet the huge
food import bill, the government had to borrow 338 million U.S.
dollars from the International Monetary Fund and the International
Development Association to meet the food import bill of 733
million dollars in the 1998-99 fiscal year, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Against a target of 350,000 tons of food import by the public
sector from the government's own resources, it had to import one
million tons due to the loss of rice crop in the last year's
severe flood. So the government had to borrow to meet the
additional cost for food import.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997-98 fiscal year, food imports in the private sector
totaled over one million tons, while in 1998-99 fiscal year, the
imports crossed three million tons.
</P>
<P>
"It is not sufficient to raise production of food in the
country, it is essential to strengthen the food security system,"
Finance Minister S.A.M.S Kabria pointed out while presenting the
national budget for the 1999-2000 fiscal year in the parliament on
June 10 this year.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh would chart out its own national food security
strategy, according to the finance minister.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 128 million, this agriculture-based South
Asian country's annual needs of food grains is over 21 million
tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
