<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Joint Press Communique on WTO (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Following is the full text of a
Sino-Japanese Joint Press Communique on China's access to the
World Trade Organization (WTO) which was issued here today by the
Chinese and Japanese government delegations:
</P>
<P>
In line with the bilateral negotiations in July 1999 on the
access of the People's Republic of China to the World Trade
Organization (WTO), the Chinese and Japanese delegations announce
that:
</P>
<P>
1. In the past several months, the Chinese delegation and the
Japanese delegation have held a series of wide-ranging, in-depth
bilateral negotiations on the service trade.
</P>
<P>
The two have successfully concluded the service trade talks
after intense negotiations. And in addition to the framework
agreement on commodities trade was reached by the two sides in
1997, China and Japan have substantially concluded all bilateral
negotiations, and the two sides are happy about this.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese side hopes that China, as a WTO member, can
further open its service trade sector, including
telecommunications and retail sales, in the next round of WTO
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side says that China is willing to participate in
the next round of talks in accordance with relevant articles of
the General Agreement on Service Trade after China becomes a WTO
member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
