<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Japan Conclude WTO Talks (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 9 (Xinhua) -- China and Japan have substantially
concluded their bilateral negotiations on China's accession to the
World Trade Organization (WTO), they announced in a joint press
communique here today at noon.
</P>
<P>
The two have successfully concluded service trade talks
following some detailed negotiations over the past several months,
the communique says.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the two reached a goods trade
protocol in 1997, and, with the current agreements, China and
Japan have substantially concluded all bilateral negotiations.
</P>
<P>
China's bid to enter the trade organization and its predecessor
has drug on for 13 years, but on Thursday, Chinese trade officials
said that bilateral negotiations on China's WTO accession have
entered the final stage.
</P>
<P>
Today's joint press communique came after Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji's meeting with Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who
arrived here Thursday afternoon for a three-day visit.
</P>
<P>
In the communique they said that they appreciate the completion
of the negotiations and are satisfied with the outcome. They have
decided to complete the necessary technical checks as soon as
possible and report the results to the WTO Secretariat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
