<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Introduce 4-stroke 3-wheelers This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- With the increase in supplementary
duty on two-stroke "baby taxis" (three-wheeled motorized vehicle),
the capital city of this South Asian nation will soon have cleaner
four-stroke three-wheelers, The Daily Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh's main importer of three-wheelers, Menoka Motors,
will import a first batch of four-stroke three-wheelers, a most
popular means of transport here, by December.
</P>
<P>
"We will first bring a test consignment of 25 taxis... In
March (next year) we will start commercial import," said Kazi
Imdad Hossain, executive director of Menoka Motors. The
newly-imposed supplementary duty on two-stroke engines in the
current fiscal year beginning July 1 has made the import of
four-stroke engines viable, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The new duty structure has discouraged us from importing those
(two-stroke engines)," said Hossain.
</P>
<P>
In the budget the parliament passed at the end of last month,
the supplementary duty on two-stroke engines, regarded as the
major air polluter in the city, has been increased from 50 percent
to 100 percent, raising the price of a two-stroke baby taxi to
135,000 taka (2,783 U.S. dollars) from 115,500 taka (2,381
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Four-stroke engines are exempted from any supplementary duty.
Uttara Motors, another importer of three-wheelers, hopes to market
the four-stroke petrol three-wheelers at a price of 140,000 taka
(2,887 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Some 35,000 two-stroke baby taxis are plying the roads in
Dhaka, emitting exhaust of petrol and unburned lubricant which is
hazardous for health. Some 1 million people commute daily on these
three-wheelers.
</P>
<P>
In order to curb the growing air pollution in the capital city,
home for some 9 million residents, the government banned import of
two-stroke baby taxis, mostly from India, last year but later
withdrew the order in the face of agitation by their owners.
</P>
<P>
The existing two-stroke taxis will take eight to 10 years to be
completely phased out, and till then, they will continue to
pollute the air and the environment, experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Phase Out Troops from S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is to phase out its troops in
Sierra Leone with the progress of the implementation of a peace
accord signed Wednesday, an aide to Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo said in Abuja Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Doyin Okupe, a press assistant to the president, told a news
briefing in the capital that Nigeria will "begin to put in place
a process of gradual and phased withdrawal of Nigerian troops from
Sierra Leone aligned with the stage by stage developmental
progress of the Lome peace agreement."
</P>
<P>
"This action will be in keeping with the electioneering
promises of President Obasanjo to get Nigerian troops back home at
the soonest possible time, without jeopardy to the peace process,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian troops form the backbone of the more than
12,000-strong west Africa peace-keeping force ECOMOG which first
intervened in Sierra Leone in 1997 to reinstate President Tajen
Kabbah after he was overthrown by his army.
</P>
<P>
But peace-keeping efforts in Sierra Leone has proved to be too
costly, especially at a time when Nigeria's own economy is
tottering.
</P>
<P>
The peace efforts have cost Nigeria hundreds of lives so far
and reportedly one million U.S. dollars a day, according to
Nigerian newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
A peace deal was signed in Togo's capital Lome Wednesday
between Sierra Leonean President Kabbah and rebel leader Foday
Sankoh, with several west African presidents including Obasanjo as
the co-signers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Safe for Visitors: Tourist Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 8 (Xinhua) -- All tourists and other visitors are
assured that it is safe and secure when they visit Kenya and the
capital Nairobi, the Kenya Tourist Board said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tourists and visitors to the country "should feel free to come
and enjoy the cool July and August temperatures," the board said
in a statement issued after the privately-owned public vehicles
known as "matatu" strike Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As the strike entered its second day, the board said, Kenyan
capital Nairobi was calm and that people were going about their
businesses as usual.
</P>
<P>
"Whether the strike will go on is unclear, what is clear,
however, is that Nairobi is safe and Kenya is safe." the board
said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the strike was only affecting commuters who have
to make use of matatus or mini-buses as means of public transport
and did not affect visitors to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The board also mentioned that visitors from most countries of
the world do not need visas if they are coming for less than 30
days, saying that those tourists already in Kenya are encouraged
to relax and enjoy their holidays.
</P>
<P>
Matatus went on strike Wednesday in protest against the
introduction of the new regulations by the Transport Licensing
Board aiming at streamlining the matatu industry in the country.
</P>
<P>
The strikers, mainly touts, attempted to disrupt the smooth
flow of traffic by burning tires in the middle of some roads
leading to the cities, including capital Nairobi and Nakuru, the
country's third largest city in the central region.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulations, the matatu touts are to be
replaced by civic council workers at bus terminuses while matatu
drivers and conductors should wear identification badges, all
matatus are to be licensed by the board and matatu routes are to
be re-allocated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
