<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0500 GMT, July 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. consumers' credit outstanding, excluding
mortgage debt, grew sharply at a 10.9 percent annual rate in May
to a seasonally adjusted 1.34 trillion dollars, the Federal
Reserve said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In May, consumers borrowed 12.1 billion dollars more than the
month before. The sharp increase in the borrowing rate follows
much smaller gains in April and March and marked the largest
increase since January when consumer credit climbed at an
annualized rate of 14 percent. (US-Consumer Credit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WELLINGTON -- United States President Bill Clinton's latest
endorsement of tariffs for New Zealand and Australian lamb imports
has met with outrage from New Zealand farmers, exporters and
politicians.
</P>
<P>
They attacked the U.S. move as "protectionist and unwarranted."
(New Zealand-US-Lamb Imports)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Spain's Economy Minister Rodrigo Rato has
proposed euro to be the currency offered to Argentine firms, the
possibility of being quoted in a near future on the Madrid Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The official suggested that in this way Argentine firms could
enter the Spanish market and be financed in euro. (Spain-Mercosur-
Euro)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The gross domestic product of the Latin American
countries will shrink 1.5 percent during the current year,
according to a report published Thursday by the Institute of
National Studies of Panama University.
</P>
<P>
But the economy will be better than last year, when the region'
s GDP dipped 2.1 percent compared with 1997, in which the economy
surged 5.2 percent, the report said. (Latin America-GDP)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Nicaragua earned last year 200 million dollars from
foreign remittance inflows, rather than 800 million dollars
announced by the Economic Commission for Latin America (CEPAL),
said Central Bank President Noe Ramirez on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Ramirez noted that 60 percent of the remittances came from the
United States and 40 percent Costa Rica. (Nicaragua-Remittance)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexico's gross domestic product (GDP) will
increase by 3 percent in 1999, analysts of the Financial Group
Banamex-Accival said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The experts said the figures was obtained from the encouraging
growth of the macro-economy in the first half of this year. (
Mexico-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia's locally incorporated banks suffered net
losses totaling 166.4 trillion rupiah (24.4 billion U.S. dollars)
in 1998, compared with the 2.3 trillion rupiah net income in 1997,
according to the latest issue of monthly magazine Info Bank.
</P>
<P>
The magazine's managing editor Eko B. Supriyanto said that the
figures were based on the 1998 financial reports published by the
banks. (Indonesia-Banks-Loss)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Foreign banks in Brazil have been actively engaged
in raising funds from the world financial market over the years
and may surpass the local banks as the number one institute in
attracting foreign financial resources into the country.
</P>
<P>
In bank-raised foreign funds in Brazil, the share of foreign
banks rose from 32.37 percent in 1993 to 46.3 in 1998 while
Brazilian banks' share went down from 67.63 percent to 53.7
percent, showed figures released Thursday by Brazil's Central Bank.
(Brazil-Foreign Banks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- The Indonesian government approved 54 investment
projects in the tourism sector in the first five months of 1999,
The Business News bulletin reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The projects composed 47 foreign investment projects worth
about 91.02 million U.S. dollars and seven domestic investment
projects worth approximately 155.82 billion rupiah (11.26 million
U.S. dollars). (Indonesia-Tourism Projects) 
</P>
