<HEADLINE> Vietnam Moves to Bolster Equitization Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Vietnamese government is moving
to bolster equitization process of the country's state-owned
enterprises, aiming at stimulating what is regarded as an ailing
economy for the remainder of the year.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government, according to Vietnam News daily
Friday, has instructed the State Treasury to write off or extend
debts owed by insolvent state-owned enterprises targeted for
equitization.
</P>
<P>
The move, to apply only to those debts classified as
"irretrievable" and which are owed to the state, is designed to
speed up the equitization process.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Minister of Planning and Investment Tran Xuan Gia
told a press conference here Thursday that those enterprises
subject to equitization, leasing and hire purchase should be
released of the debts.
</P>
<P>
Another way to promote the equitization process, Gia said, was
to lift the limit on the number of shares that can be bought by
domestic buyers.
</P>
<P>
He said that a government meeting in Hanoi last Monday and
Tuesday, held to review operations and look at the remainder of
the year, concurred that the first six months had met with
difficulties which saw higher unemployment, a decline of incomes
in certain business sectors, particularly in rural and flood and
drought-stricken areas, and an increase in social evils in some
areas.
</P>
<P>
These factors combined to cause concern among the population
and minimize economic growth rates.
</P>
<P>
"The government recognizes the need to devise contingencies in
case of harder times ahead," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government also decided to release extra
budgetary investment to accelerate ongoing construction of
development projects and more bank loans to farmers to increase
rural purchasing power for the remainder of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
