<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Banks in Brazil Increase Fund Raising From World Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Foreign banks in Brazil have been
actively engaged in raising funds from the world financial market
over the years and may surpass the local banks as the number one
institute in attracting foreign financial resources into the
country.
</P>
<P>
In bank-raised foreign funds in Brazil, the share of foreign
banks rose from 32.37 percent in 1993 to 46.3 in 1998 while
Brazilian banks' share went down from 67.63 percent to 53.7
percent, showed figures released Thursday by Brazil's Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank said that the funds raised by both Brazilian
and foreign banks from the world financial market increased from
11.031 billion U.S. dollars in 1993 to 58.128 billion dollars in
1998.
</P>
<P>
In the period, the amount of funds raised by foreign banks grew
129 percent annually from 3.6 billion dollars to 26.913 billion
dollars while Brazilian banks' amount merely posted an average
annual growth of 64 percent from 7.4 billion dollars to 31.21
billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
