<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Rhinoceros Fossil on Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The fossil skeleton of a rhinoceros
dating back 3 million years ago was recently restored and shown in
public in Xunyi County of northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
"This was the first integrated rhinoceros fossil ever assembled
in the world," said Xue Xiangxi, a Chinese archaeologist who heads
the effort to assemble the skeleton.
</P>
<P>
Also on display was a sabre-tooth elephant fossil assembled
earlier. The elephant is 8.45 meters long and 4.3 meters high. Its
front teeth had a length of 3.17 meters.
</P>
<P>
The rhinoceros skeleton is 4.8 meters long and 3.1 meters high.
It was composed of 62 fossils which were linked up with armor
plates and iron bars.
</P>
<P>
Restoration of the rhinoceros fossil is of great value to the
study of ancient geology, physiognomy and climate of Loess Plateau
and to the evolution of living things in ancient times in the
middle reaches of Yellow River, said Guan Jian, a research fellow
of the Beijing Nature Museum.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it is a rare sample for disseminating popular science,
he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
