<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Reports Big Increases in Tax Revenue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen City of south China's
Guangdong Province collected a total of 6.82 billion yuan in local
tax revenues in the first six months of the year, up 14.9 percent
from the same period last year, local sources said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the city also collected 12.1 billion yuan in
state tax revenues from January to June, up 10.6 percent from the
first six months of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Of the total state tax revenues, 10.78 billion yuan went to
the state coffers. The Shenzhen State Taxation Bureau also paid
the city's foreign trade companies 420 million yuan in tax rebates.
</P>
<P>
Local taxation officials attributed the big increases to rapid
expansion of the city's electronics and information, commerce,
power sectors, big increases in stamp taxes of active securities
transactions in the wake of a bullish bourse, and a sharp increase
in import tariffs recovered from crackdowns on smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Local taxation departments have also made efforts to improve
service to facilitate tax payers.
</P>
<P>
China started to introduce a tax sharing system between the
Central Government and governments at local levels beginning in
1994 by setting up two taxation bodies -- the State taxation
bureaus and local taxation bureaus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
