<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar to Allow Logging for Wood-Based Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmar authorities will allow
both local citizens and foreigners to fell trees required for
establishing wood-based industries for the production and export
of value-added wood products, according to a notice of the
state-run Myanmar Timber Enterprise (MTE) here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Logging for a minimum of 20 years is guaranteed in Dawei, Myeik
and Kawthoung areas and adjacent islands in the southern coastal
Tanintharyi division, the notice said.
</P>
<P>
The notice urged entrepreneurs to take special care in the
extraction to avoid depletion of the resources and adverse effect
on the environment of the islands and the region.
</P>
<P>
However, clear felling will not be allowed, it said, adding
that only those logs meeting the girth limits set by the Forest
Department can be felled.
</P>
<P>
The MTE has been cooperating with local and foreign firms to
establish wood-based industries in the country. So far, seven
foreign firms from China, France, South Korea, Malaysia, Norway
and Thailand have reached agreements with the MTE, setting up
plywood, molding and furniture factories in Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The MTE is the sole organization allowed to extract timber out
of forests in the country and it undertakes logging,
transportation, milling, processing, distribution of products
within the country, and exportation.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar restricts export of logs and bans the private sector
from exporting teak logs after the enactment of the country's
Forest Law in 1992. However, export of value-added wood products
is encouraged.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar exported 133,717 cubic meters of teak and 235,739 cubic
meters of hardwood in 1998, through which a total of 123.6 million
U.S. dollars of foreign exchange earning was obtained, according
to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is rich in forest resources with forest covering 50
percent of its land area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
