<HEADLINE> Asia Delegated May Walk Out of FIFA Congress: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Asian countries may walk out of
Friday's congress of soccer's world governing body FIFA in Los
Angeles, in protest over the allocation of berths in the 2002
World Cup's qualifying tournament, their leader said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"This is a decision of great gravity for world football and
for Mr. (FIFA President Sepp) Blatter, but our members have shown
great solidarity," said Malaysian Peter Velappan, general
secretary of the Asian Football Confederation, was quoted by
Reuters news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
"No one should mess about with Asia. All of this has been
totally ignored and (World Cup) seats given away to those who don'
t deserve them," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asia had earlier threatened to boycott the qualifying
tournament for the 2002 World Cup because FIFA had not been given
them enough berths.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after an emergency meeting of Asian
delegates attending Friday's FIFA congress in Los Angeles said
that Asia had no choice but to give up its two existing qualifying
positions and go into the tournament solely with Japan and South
Korea, the co-hosts of the 2002 World Cup finals and thus
automatic qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
Velappan, however, indicated that Asia might change its mind
on the boycott if FIFA reconsidered the allocation of berths, the
reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
