<HEADLINE> Rios Dumped from Swiss Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Third seed Marcelo Rios, who
returned to the tennis court from a five-week injury lay-off,
conceeded 7-6, 7-6 to Morocco's Younes El Aynaoui in the second
round of the Swiss Open in Gstaad, Switzerland, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean's departure combined with earlier exits by top seed
Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil, number two Alex Corretja of Spain and
number four Greg Rusedski of Britain, left Spain's Felix Mantilla
as the highest remaining seed.
</P>
<P>
Mantilla, the fifth seed and 1997 Swiss champion, entered the
quarter-finals with a 6-2, 6-0 victory over another Moroccan
Hicham Arazi.
</P>
<P>
Seventh seed Mariano Zabaleta of Argentina also joined the
exodus of seeds, falling 6-7, 7-6, 6-3 to Italy's Andrea Gaudenzi.
</P>
<P>
Playing in his first tournament since a quarter-final loss to
Dominik Hrbaty at the French Open, Rios showed plenty of
determination against El Aynaoui but his game lacked the sharpness
that helped him to titles in Hamburg and St Poelten earlier this
season.
</P>
<P>
El Aynaoui will face sixth seed Francisco Clavet of Spain, who
beat American qualifier Don Johnson, ranked 522 in the world, 6-4
6-4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
