<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Program to Boost Power Generation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has launched a program to
invest 175 billion rupees (2.5 billion U.S. dollars) to step up
power generation within the next seven years to keep pace with the
growing demand for electricity, said a Electricity Board spokesman
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The demand for electricity has been increasing at an annual
rate of 10 percent since 1990 and the demand is expected to grow
at about the same rate during the next few years, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said about 160,000 new consumers are connected to
the existing electricity distribution network every year while the
demand for more power by existing consumers is also rising.
</P>
<P>
The country's electricity generating system comprising 1,135
megawatt hydro electric power and 478 megawatt thermal power can
provide electricity needs to about 4,800 gigawatt hours.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, a 40 megawatt thermal power plant is
proposed to be built at Sapugaskanda in the suburbs of Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The Kelanitissa thermal power plant in Colombo will be boosted
by a 150 megawatt Combined Cycle Plant at a cost of 1,850 million
rupees (26.4 million dollars) funded by the Overseas Economic
Cooperation Fund (OECF) of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Work has also begun on a 15 billion rupees (214 million
dollars) hydro power station with a capacity of 70 megawatts at
Kukule Ganga.
</P>
<P>
The West Coast Coal Fired Power plant at Kalpitiya, Puttalam in
northwestern Sri Lanka, will come on line also with funds from the
OECF of Japan.
</P>
<P>
Additionally, plans are under way to commence village and
estate hydro electricity programs to meet the increasing demand
for power.
</P>
<P>
Only 52 percent of Sri Lanka's households now have access to
electricity. The Sri Lankan government has decided to observe
1999-2009 as a decade of power development in a bid to provide
every household with electricity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
