<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Controls Pests with Ecological Means </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Every morning this summer, the first
thing Yasen Tohuti, a cotton grower in northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, did was to pick up the poplar branches he
put in his cotton field the day before and shook off dead
bollworms from the poplar branch leaves.
</P>
<P>
"I had to deal with these insects with the unique method
because the more they nibble the less I earn," said Yasen, a 36-
year-old farmer of Uygur Nationality.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the several non-chemical methods the local
farmers use to prevent and control pests and is being popularized
in Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
As the largest cotton producer in China, Xinjiang grows cotton
on 980,000 hectares of land, which yield an annual output of 1.3
million tons, making up one third of the nation's total. Nearly
one third of local farmers' annual income comes from cotton
production.
</P>
<P>
At present, the majority of cotton growers in Xinjiang would
like to control pests with non-toxic or biological means. Some put
up light bulbs in their cotton fields as they know bollworm loves
to swirl around lights. When the bollworms touched the metal wires
twined on the bulbs, they will get an electric shock and die.
</P>
<P>
As aphids is attracted to yellow color, farmers hang up plates
brushed with yellow paint in the fields. When the worms touch the
plates, they would get stuck on the plates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, farmers keep insects out of the cotton fields by
inter-planting crops to create natural enemy of the insects. They
also dig up soil and use water irrigation method to drown insects.
</P>
<P>
"These measures cause no pollution and are good for the
ecological environment," said Zhong Yanlong, an agricultural
specialist.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists speak highly of the insect-control method by
ecological means. They said cotton fields account for one seventh
of the oases on the vast desert in Xinjiang. The new method is of
vital importance to controlling desert encroachment in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
