<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Local Banks Lose 24.4B Dollars in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's locally incorporated
banks suffered net losses totaling 166.4 trillion rupiah (24.4
billion U.S. dollars) in 1998, compared with the 2.3 trillion
rupiah net income in 1997, according to the latest issue of
monthly magazine Info Bank.
</P>
<P>
The magazine's managing editor Eko B. Supriyanto said that the
figures were based on the 1998 financial reports published by the
banks.
</P>
<P>
As many as 168 banks were included in the magazine's report,
but only 158 of them were assessed because the other 10 banks did
not publish balance sheets for the period.
</P>
<P>
The above figure would increase by about 50 trillion rupiah to
216 trillion rupiah (30.8 billion dollars) in net losses if it
included also the losses suffered by these 10 banks, Supriyanto
was quoted by The Jakarta Post Friday as saying.
</P>
<P>
The 10 banks include the four state Banks (Bank Bapindo, Bank
Bumi Daya, Bank Exim and Bank Dagang Negara) now in the process of
being merged into newly established Bank Mandiri.
</P>
<P>
The remaining six banks are three provincial banks and three
private banks.
</P>
<P>
The magazine also said the other three state banks, namely,
Bank Negara Indonesia, Bank Rakyat Indonesia and Bank Tabungan
Negara contributed a total of 84.4 trillion rupiah (12 billion
dollars) to the figure.
</P>
<P>
"State banks are definitely the major contributors to the big
total net loss figure of the 168 national banks," Supriyanto said.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
