<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Set Up 150 Computer Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
launched a program to set up at least 150 computer centers
islandwide by year 2000 to offer 150,000 school leavers and young
job aspirants an opportunity to acquire competency in computer
science, media sources said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister Richard Pathirana was quoted as saying that
the entire project will cost 450 million rupees (6.34 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The centers which will be equipped with the latest facilities
will be designed to accommodate 1,000 students each.
</P>
<P>
Already fifty centers have been set up by the ministry and
45,000 young people have completed their one-year training course.
Over 100 such centers will be set up by the end of this year for a
student intake of 125,000 per year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The project has been launched as school children find it
difficult to gain computer literacy, vital for employment, during
school days due to limited opportunity, lack of time and
financial problems.
</P>
<P>
The computer center program was launched by the Sri Lankan
government in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
