<HEADLINE> Latin American GDP to Shrink 1.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product of
the Latin American countries will shrink 1.5 percent during the
current year, according to a report published Thursday by the
Institute of National Studies of Panama University.
</P>
<P>
But the economy will be better than last year, when the region'
s GDP dipped 2.1 percent compared with 1997, in which the economy
surged 5.2 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Due to the decline of Brazilian economy, the largest one in
Latin America, the region is facing a relatively difficult
situation, the report said, since the private investment to the
region will reduce from 83.1 billion U.S. dollars in 1998 to 51.5
billion dollars in 1999. 
</P>
