<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Changing Face Of Cancer In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The incidence of esophageal,
stomach, nasopharynx, and cervical cancers has dropped in China,
but lung, breast, colon and rectal cancers have been on the rise
in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
According to one study, deaths from cervical cancer in the
1990s were down 65 percent in urban areas and 78 percent in rural
areas from those in the 1970s, and esophageal cancer rate was down
44.34 in urban China and 14.16 percent in rural China,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that this has a great deal to do with changing
lifestyles and the ecology. People today eat less pickled food and
more fresh vegetables and fruits.
</P>
<P>
A lack of physical exercise and the intake of too much fatty
food may account for the large increase in breast and colon
cancers, while pollution, radiation, excessive drinking, and
certain medicines may also be a cause.
</P>
<P>
However, one study found the surprising fact that more women
who are not smokers suffer or die from lung cancer, something that
scientists say could be caused by too much cooking with coal or
natural gas and frying too much food.
</P>
<P>
Cooking with coal for more than 15 years has been found to
increase cancer incidence by 125 percent, while women with shorter
menstrual cycles have been found to be more likely to have lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
The greater intake of fresh vegetables and fruits and the
elimination of pollutants in the house can reduce the death rate
of lung cancer, scientists suggest, and an improved diet, more
physical exercise, and the prevention of obesity can reduce the
cancer rate by some 30 to 40 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
