<HEADLINE> Chinese Women Spikers Make Semi-final in Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese spikers initiated
the quarter-finals of the women's volleyball tournament by beating
their Thai peers 3-1, booking the first semi-final berth at the
20th World University Games here Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Despite its lack of systematic training due to an assembly in a
hurry for the Games, the Chinese established a 18-12 lead before
taking the first set 25-23 in 20 minutes in front of dozens of
spectators.
</P>
<P>
Yet, the second set witnessed a see-saw battle until setter
Feng Kun was fielded in to pull the Chinese ahead with five
straight points from 11-12 to 16-12 and sealed the set 25-16 for a
comfortable 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
In the third set, the Thais exerted every effort to rally from
a four-point deficit at 7-11 to a 26-all tie, before taking the
heated set 28-26 in their favor.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese rushed ahead from 7-all in the decisive fourth set
to 19-11 before sealing the competitions 25-17.
</P>
<P>
"The Thais resorted to aggressive serves and seldom committed
mistakes," said Zhen Jiucheng, manager of the Chinese team.
</P>
<P>
"It's really better for the Chinese to lose one set as their
opponents in later stages are much more strong," said Zhen. "We
are very rusty in team work which is the key for success,
especially in volleyball, just because we don't have enough time
for systematic training."
</P>
<P>
"But our players are of great potentials, and I dare bet to put
them in the top three in the national league should I be given
three months," he added.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, China will face Japan in the semi-final
Friday evening as Japan routed the Chinese Taipei 25-20, 26-24, 22-
25 and 25-17.
</P>
<P>
The other semi-final pits France against Russia after France
scored its straight-set win over Spain 25-19, 25-23 and 25-23,
while Russia won a full-set victory over Romania 16-25, 25-23, 25-
27, 25-23 and 15-4.
</P>
<P>
In the matches for the ninth to 16th places, the United States
defeated Switzerland 25-19, 25-18 and 25-19, Canada outwitted
Ukraine 19-25,20-25, 25-21, 25-22 and 15-8, the Czech Republic
savored an easy win over South Africa 25-10, 25-6 and 25-5 while
Brazil was protracted to five sets before beating Sweden 20-25, 25-
23, 24-26, 25-21 and 15-8. 
</P>
