At a press conference, FA spokesman Steve Double announced
another player, Reading's Byron Glasgow, had tested positive for
recreational drugs.
</P>
<P>
The results of the tests mean that the FA will increase the
amount of random drug testing during the following season.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on BBC Radio 5 Live, Double confirmed that the
increase in testing was at the request of Premiership clubs. "At
the moment, our problem is the same that faces any parent of a
young boy or girl - the drugs are out there. We are encouraged by
the fact that during the last five years there has been a steady
decline in the amount of positives," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
