<HEADLINE> U.S. Military Chief Denies Moving Troops From Panama to Honduras </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, July 8 (Xinhua)-- Chief of the U.S. South Command,
General Charles Wilhelm, denied an eventual move of his troops in
Panama to Honduras, local media reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Wilhelm said that the South Command, the U.S. operational force
for Latin America, will be based in Miami following dismantling
American military installations at the Canal zone in Panama, which
is to gain the control of the canal by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
He met with Honduras Defense Minister Edgardo Dumas Rodriguez
here on Wednesday. The two military chiefs discussed cooperation
on Cuban issues.
</P>
<P>
Wilhelm said that future cooperation will be concentrated on
technical assistance, providing supplies and equipment.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, United States gave more than 400 million dollars
of military aid to Honduras within the framework of its anti-
gurerrilla warfare for Central America.
</P>
<P>
General Wilhelm denied that Palmerola base, about 80 kilometers
north of Tegucigalpa, is to be converted into a center for anti-
drug traffic in Central America, but admitted it has been used as
a base for certain special operations against drug-traffic.
</P>
<P>
The base at Palmerola was built by the United States in the
past decade for "dissuading" operations against Nicaragua's
Sandinista movement and El Salvador's guerrilla forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
