<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Denies Pressing Man United </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Football's world governing body FIFA
has denied pressing Manchester United to compete in their brand
new World Team Championship rather than the FA Cup.
</P>
<P>
The row over which trophies the treble-winners will compete for
next season continues to drag on - with everyone from the domestic
cup's sponsors to the manager of United's rivals Arsenal having
their say.
</P>
<P>
Players' union chief Gordon Taylor also entered the fray on
Thursday, as United boss Sir Alex Ferguson insisted again the club
will not change its mind.
</P>
<P>
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger said United's decision to pull
out was "slowly killing the FA Cup" while PFA boss Taylor insisted
the government had put pressure on United.
</P>
<P>
"I remember 1958 and, days after the Munich air crash,
Manchester United had a team playing in the FA Cup," said the
union chief.
</P>
<P>
"They then had a team in the European Cup and they stayed in
both competitions.
</P>
<P>
"It's incredible to think that four decades on they have
dropped out of this FA Cup with the resources they have."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile FIFA president Sepp Blatter, the man behind the
international event, said the withdrawal saddened him.
</P>
<P>
"I regret that because the FA Cup is the cup competition in the
world," he told BBC Radio 5 Live's Inside Edge program
</P>
<P>
"But it was their decision. We have never had any contact with
Manchester United directly from FIFA to the club because we went
through the UEFA channel."
</P>
<P>
Blatter believes that the inclusion of United in the tournament
will add to the quality of competition in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
"The qualification for this was through the confederations and
we would like to have the champions from each one," he explained.
</P>
<P>
That could be unlikely in the long-term, with UEFA chief
Lennart Johansson warning that the European champions'
participation could be a one-off.
</P>
<P>
"For this once, we are going to Brazil out of loyalty to the
football family," he said. "But we cannot guarantee participation
in the future."
</P>
<P>
FA Cup sponsors AXA appear determined to get United into their
competition, whatever it takes.
</P>
<P>
One of their ideas was to fly United's English opponents to
Brazil midway through the new competition.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously we are aware that there is considerable feeling
amongst fans the length and breadth of the country," explained AXA
spokesman Phil Hickley said.
</P>
<P>
"This one was one of a number of private and initial ideas,
which have not been discussed with the FA. We have not even
attempted to consider their feasibility, and of course, Manchester
United would have to take part in any decision."
</P>
<P>
FA spokesman Steve Double immediately dismissed the plan. "It
is an amusing idea but completely unworkable," he said. "It would
mean the competition would be taken out of English football's
jurisdiction."
</P>
<P>
And despite all the talk, United boss Ferguson is unmoved. "
Obviously a lot of concern has been expressed by various bodies
such as the government, FIFA and UEFA," he said while in Glasgow
to open a new media center at Hampden Park.
</P>
<P>
"But we took everything into consideration when we made the
decision and now it has been taken we have to get on with it.
There are all sorts of rumours flying about but we have to deal
with the facts and get on with our job," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
