<HEADLINE> Americans Increase Swimming Golds to 14 in Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Swimming power United States
choked up another three gold medals on Thursday, enlarging its
gold tally to 14 out of 29 gold medals offered in the five-day
competitions at the 20th World University Games here.
</P>
<P>
The day's other two gold medals were bagged home by Japan who
also increased its swimming tally to five, followed by Russia with
three, and the Czech Republic and Australia with two each. Spain,
Romania and South Africa had one gold medal apiece from the pool.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Hannan initiated the American golden haul by taking the
men's 200-meter individual medley in two minutes 4.42 seconds
after overtaking Peter Mankoi of Slovenia in the 100-meter mark.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Philip Weiss finished second in 2:04.67, ahead of
Japanese Takahiro Mori in 2:04.94.
</P>
<P>
Tomoko Hagiwara triumphed in the day's second event of the
women's 200m medley by touching home first in 2:16.21, beating
German Sabine Klenz to second in 2:17.54 and Canadian Elizabeth
Warden to third in 2:18.06.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. dominance in the pool was regained as Beau Wiebel and
Tate Blahnik finished 1-2 in 2:01.52 and 2:01.70 respectively in
the men's 200m backstroke, with Canada taking the bronze medal
through Greg Hamm in 2:01.73.
</P>
<P>
Cara Lane and Julie Varozza repeated the 1-2 finish for the
United States in the women's 1,500m freestyle with comfortable
margins as they clocked in 16:32.04 and 16:33.92 respectively
while Hana Cerna of the Czech Republic finished in a distant third
place in 16:35.56.
</P>
<P>
Japan rounded up the last title of the day by taking the women'
s 4x100m medley relay through Inada Norico, Nakashima Kazue,
Hagiwara Tomoko and Imoto Naoko.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese quartet finished in their winning time of 4:09.90,
followed by the United States in 4:11.82 and Ukraine in 4:15.06.
