<HEADLINE> Philippines' Largest Corporations Post Higher Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- All but one of the top ten largest
corporations in the Philippines registered increased sales in
1998, the year Asian economies were hit hardest by the region-wide
economic crisis, Business World reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted data released Thursday by the country's
Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) as saying that the 10 had
combined sales of 576.5 billion pesos (14.4 billion U.S. dollars),
an increase of 22.5 percent over the sum in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Total profits doubled to 29.54 billion pesos (739 million
dollars) from the record of 1997, SEC said.
</P>
<P>
However, according to SEC, two of the 10 suffered financial
losses in 1998, while two of the eight that reported profits
experienced thinner gains.
</P>
<P>
SEC's data showed that the top ten list was made up of the same
names as in the preceding year, with state-owned National Power
Corp. and Manila Electric Co. maintaining their No.1 and No. 2
positions respectively.
</P>
<P>
In terms of profits, food and beverage giant San Miguel Corp.
remained on top with 24.41 billion pesos (610 million dollars)
while the Philippine Amusement Gaming Corp. kept its second
ranking with profits of 6.73 billion pesos (168 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The top ten list is part of the SEC's annual listing of the
largest 1,000 corporations in terms of sales, the paper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
