<HEADLINE> Argentine, British Foreign Ministers to Meet Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Argentine Foreign Minister
Guido di Tella announced Thursday that he will meet his British
counterpart Robin Cook next Tuesday in London to continue
negotiations on the renewal of flights to the Malvinas Islands.
</P>
<P>
Refuting a newspaper report, he said imminent announcements to
renew flights between Argentina's mainland and the Malvinas are
not to be expected.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations concerning these matters have been frozen since
1982, and to revitalize the process needs time and patience, he
noted, adding that a constructive climate now prevailed for
continuing such talks between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers met three times last week to discuss
the issue, with  Argentina favoring restarting flights to the
Malvinas via its mainland territory in order that Argentines may
travel there with national documents. But the British government
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
Flights to the Malvinas, known in Britain as the Falkland
Islands, were suspended since the 1982 war between the two
countries over the sovereignty of the archipelago. 
