<HEADLINE> U.N. Security Council Hails Peace Accord in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council on
Thursday evening "warmly welcomed" a peace accord signed by Sierra
Leone's warring parties, saying that "the United Nations will have
a key role to play in the implementation of this agreement."
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the 15-
nation Security Council, Hasma Agam of Malaysia, said, "Members of
the Council stressed that the signing of this agreement is a
significant achievement for all concerned, and a historic turning
point for Sierra Leone and its people."
</P>
<P>
The statement came at the end of a closed-door session of the
Security Council, which began on Thursday evening to discuss the
latest development in the efforts to end the civil war in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held only one day after the warring Sierra
Leonean parties signed in Togo a peace accord, which formally ends
eight years of civil war that has killed tens of thousands and
maimed many more.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Security Council urged both the government of
Sierra Leone and the rebel Revolutionary United Front (RUF) to
ensure that the accord's provisions are implemented.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council also paid tribute to the key role
played by the ECOMOG (West African peacekeepers) in Sierra Leone,
without whose commitment this achievement would not have been
possible," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the Security Council called upon the international
community to assist Sierra Leone in their efforts at
reconciliation and reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
Voicing his welcome to the peace accord, U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, who was on a visit to the West African nation, said
Thursday that the peace deal signed this week to end the civil war
in the country was an encouraging sign for peace across the whole
continent of Africa.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed by Sierra Leonean President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah and RUF leader Foday Sankoh in Togo's capital of Lome late
Wednesday. Francis Okelo, the U.N. special representative for
Sierra Leone, also inked the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The fighting raged until just six weeks ago, when a cease-fire
was signed, and rebels were blamed for the bulk of the atrocities
against unarmed civilians, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Annan, while visiting Sierra Leone, held separate talks with
Kabbah, U.N. observers and officers in the Nigerian-led ECOMOG,
which will form the core of a new peacekeeping force, U.N.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Since the latter part of the war, ECOMOG has stationed some 15,
000 soldiers in Sierra Leone and has been the strongest military
force defending the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
