<HEADLINE> Fighting Kills Over 70 in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, July 8 (Xinhua) -- More than 70 people were feared dead
on Thursday in a heavy fighting between the government forces and
the rebels near the country's capital of Bogota.
</P>
<P>
About 40 government soldiers and 37 Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombian guerrillas died in the battle that began at dawn
around the Andean village of Gutierrez, 15 miles (25 km) south of
Bogota, an army spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another 96 troops were missing after they lost radio
contact with the rest of their company shortly after midday, she
added.
</P>
<P>
"There are a large number of dead on both sides. I don't know
what the rebels' targets were but they were coming toward Bogota
and were going to carry out attacks in Bogota or the outskirts,"
armed forces chief Gen. Fernando Tapias told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"This is an act of war," he added.
</P>
<P>
The fighting, which was the worst in a series of recent clashes
between the government forces and the rebels, occurred after the
two sides agreed Tuesday to postpone for two weeks their peace
talks that started in early January.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations are aimed at ending Colombia's long-running
war that has claimed more than 35,000 lives in just 10 years.
</P>
