<HEADLINE> Hosts Spain Enters Universiade Basketball Quarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 8 (Xinhua) -- The teams of Spain, the United
States, Yugoslavia and Russia remained unbeaten to top their
respective groups as the men's basketball preliminaries which
concluded Thursday evening at the 20th World University Games here.
</P>
<P>
Spain routed Ireland 97-54 in its last outing for its fifth
straight win and will face Group D runner-up of Brazil who
outscored Finland 82-50 for four wins against one loss.
</P>
<P>
In Group B, the United States lived up to its reputation by
beating Greece 91-72 for a clean slate, facing its quarter-final
opponent of Group C second-placers Canada who defeated the
Netherlands 85-55 for three wins against one loss after Germany
withdrew from the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia remains as a European power as it recorded its
fourth straight victory of 98-38 against South Africa to claim the
top spot in Group C early on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslavian cagers will face Group B runners-up Lithuania
who defeated the Czech Republic 87-79 for four wins against one
loss suffered against the United States.
</P>
<P>
Russia was ushered in the title of Group D after it beat
Britain 80-71 and will clash against Group A second-placers Mexico
who outscored Hong Kong, China 103-60 for its fourth victory.
</P>
<P>
In the other games of the day, China remained winless after it
lost to Peru 87-88, Japan recorded its first-ever win of 68-47,
South Korea lost for the fourth time 81-82 to Nigeria, and Turkey
beat Bulgaria 66-47.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Bulgaria qualified for the competitions for the 9-
16th places from Group A, while Greece and the Czech Republic
finished third and fourth in Group B.
</P>
<P>
Group C also produced two teams of the Netherlands and Japan
for the 9-16th places competitions, while Britain and Finland
qualified from Group D.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, China, Hong Kong, China were the only winless
sides in the preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
Joining them in the exodus are Ireland, Nigeria, South Korea
and Peru. 
</P>
</TEXT>
