<HEADLINE> Universiade Round-up: Chinese Wins First Judo Title in Universiade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PALMA, Spain, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Chinese judoka Yuan Hua took
the first judo title when she triumphed in the women's over 78-kg
category of the judo competitions which started here Thursday
afternoon at the 20th World University Games here.
</P>
<P>
However, the United States still reapt the most of four gold
medals out of the 13 golds at stake of the day, by winnng three
from the swimming pool and one from the women's 10,000 meters
through Leigh Daniel as the track and field also started on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yuan Hua, 25, defeated Russian T. Dongouzachvi by ippon as the
four-minute final clicked towards its ending at the Principes de
Espanal.
</P>
<P>
"I cared nothing of defense as I took the initiatives
throughout the final," said Yuan Hua who attained her debutant
title in the world junior championship in 1992 in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
"The gold medal is surely within my expectataion because I beat
her in the world military championships last August in St.
Petersburg,"said the native of Liaoning province, an Asian
champion last year in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
In other three judo titles taken away on Thursday, Frenchwoman
Lebrun Celine outpowered Romanian Richter Simona in the 78-kg
category and Japanese Munet Yasuyuki defeated Dutchman Van Der
Geest Dennis to take the men's over 100-kg title, with the men's
100-kg title went to Portugal's Soares Pedro who beat Ukrainian
Gorbokon Igor.
</P>
<P>
The United States choked up another three gold medals,
enlarging its swimming gold tally to 14 out of 29 gold medals
offered in the five-day competitions.
</P>
<P>
The day's other two gold medals were bagged home by Japan who
also increased its swimming tally to five, followed by Russia with
three, both the Czech Republic and Australia with two, while Spain,
Romania and South Africa with one gold medal apiece in the pool.
</P>
<P>
Thomas Hannan initiated the American haul of gold medals by
taking the men's 200-meter medley in 2:04.42 before Tomoko
Hagiwara triumphed in the women's 200m individual medley in 2:16.
21.
</P>
<P>
Beau Wiebel and Tate Blahnik claimed the top two places in 2:01.
52 and 2:01.70 respectively in the men's 200m backstroke for the
United States and Cara Lane and Julie Varozza repeated the 1-2
finish in the women's 1,500m freestyle as they clocked in 16:32.04
and 16:33.92 respectively while Japan rounded up the women's
4x100m medley relay in 4:09.90.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Jay Y. Cumba took the other track and field gold as she
threw to a winning distance of 18.70 meters in the shot put finals,
and Italian Maria Vezzail won the women's individual foil fencing
title by beating Aida Mohamed of Hungary to second.
</P>
<P>
From the last final of the evening, Ioulia Pakhalina of Russia
took the women's one-meter springboard diving title with 287.250
points,while her compatriot Irina Lashko finished second in 285.
210 points. 
