<HEADLINE> Tibetans Enjoying Greater Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, July 9 (Xinhua) -- Since 1956, Tibet has made 72 local
laws and 71 sets of local government resolutions with the power of
law that consider the ethnic, cultural and local features of
Tibetans, according to a local official.
</P>
<P>
Tibet started its democratic reforms in 1959 after the Dalai
Lama's failed rebellion and today the Tibetans enjoy complete
freedom that could not have been dreamed of by their forefathers
under the old feudalistic serf system.
</P>
<P>
Even bigamy, which could land most Chinese in jail for several
years, is allowed among Tibetans if they married before China's
first marriage law took effect in 1950. The local law is flexible
in the matter of marriage, and Tibetans who married in the early
years can maintain or change their marital status.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the flexible regional rules also allow Tibetans to
go marry at the age of 20, in the case of men, and 18 in the case
of women. Under the national marriage law, the majority of Chinese
adults are not legally allowed to take a spouse until 22 for men,
and 20 for women.
</P>
<P>
Tibetans are free to do anything lawful, including using their
mother tongue both at home and during official rites, as well as
to elect officials at the grass-roots levels.
</P>
<P>
More than 90 percent of eligible Tibetan voters take part in
regular township and county level elections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
