<HEADLINE> Fiat Voices Confidence on Deal With Mitsubishi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Fiat Chairman Paolo Fresco Thursday
voiced confidence on Wednesday's deal with the Japanese car-marker
Mitsubishi to jointly produce a new four-wheel-drive sports
utility car in Italy.
</P>
<P>
"It's above all a reinforcement," Fresco said at the annual
general meeting of the Italian Association of Motor Car
Manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Fiat in recent months has denied rumors of deals with Renault
and Ford.
</P>
<P>
The head of Fiat's car division, Roberto Testore, said he was
"very satisfied" with the deal with the Japanese car-maker.
</P>
<P>
As for possible further cooperation with Mitsubishi in the
field of joint engine development, Testore said, "We'll see, we're
working on it. It's too early to say we'll get a deal, but it's
likely."
</P>
<P>
Fiat will invest 250 billion lire (about 135 million U.S.
dollars) in the city-jeep project with Mitsubishi. It will be
responsible for the car's design and styling, while Mitsubishi,
with its expertise in four-wheel-drive vehicles, will produce the
chassis and engine.
</P>
<P>
Production is scheduled to begin in 2001 at the plant near the
Italian northeast city of Turin. The two groups plan to build
30,000 of the cars each year, taking roughly 10 percent of the
European market in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The car will allow Fiat to complete its range of vehicles and
at the same time renew Mitsubishi's range of four-wheel-drive
vehicles. 
</P>
