<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disarmament Agenda Remains Unfinished: U.N. Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 8 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking United
Nations official Thursday called for "sustainable disarmament" as
the world is facing globalization of the arms industry and growing
arms trade.
</P>
<P>
The globalization of the arms industry generates new threats
and new insecurities, said U.N. Under-Secretary-General for
Disarmament Affairs Jayantha Dhanapala.
</P>
<P>
As the U.N. pursues sustainable development, so can it work to
foster sustainable disarmament, he told Friedrich Ebert Foundation
in New York.
</P>
<P>
Dhanapala said disarmament agenda remains unfinished because
</P>
<P>
-- The treaties banning chemical and biological weapons are not
universal while over 30,000 nuclear weapons reportedly remain in
military arsenals around the world;
</P>
<P>
-- The so-called "peace dividend" remains elusive when the use
of high-tech weaponry in modern warfare such as recent wars in the
Persian Gulf and the Balkans encourages weapons proliferation and
"potentially to new arms races;"
</P>
<P>
-- The global arms trade grew 36 percent from 1995 to 1997
against a 11.2 percent decline in the decade before 1995, and
"ongoing efforts to expand NATO (the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization) and to modernize existing arsenals will no doubt
encourage further increases;"
</P>
<P>
-- The global arms industry, particularly in the Atlantic area,
is undergoing a wave of mergers and acquisitions in its post-Cold
War consolidation; and
</P>
<P>
-- European countries will likely increase research and
development in the defense sector if they follow the U.S. and
expand R&AMP;D on missile defense.
</P>
<P>
Under the circumstances, Dhanapala said, a "revolutions in
disarmament affairs" must accompany the U.N. performance of its
duties under the Charter in international peace and security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990709.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worldwide Outsourcing Services Grow: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Worldwide outsourcing services
grow fast on its way to blowing by the marker of 100 billion U.S.
dollars, according to a report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, spending topped 99 billion dollars, and by 2003, it
will explode to more than 151 billion dollars, said the U.S.
market research firm International Data Corporation (IDC).
</P>
<P>
Explaining the rapid growth, the IDC said that economic factors
such as globalization, privatization, deregulation and
technological innovation have increased competition in many
industries and regions across the world. "To remain competitive,
many companies outsource as a way to reduce costs, increase
efficiencies, and refocus critical resources," the firm said.
</P>
<P>
According to the IDC, the majority of worldwide outsourcing
spending occurs within the United States. In 1998, U.S. companies
spent 51.5 billion dollars, accounting for almost 52 percent of
all outsourcing spending worldwide. By 2003, the United States
will spend more than 81 billion dollars annually for outsourcing,
almost 54 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
In the rest of the world, information systems outsourcing
markets are also growing fast, at a torrid 26.9 percent compound
annual growth rate through 2003. Asia-Pacific will increase its
spending at a 15 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The IDC said that factors contributed to the fast growth in the
rest of the world include small and midsized companies' increasing
PC use and dramatic growth of the Internet in some countries.
</P>
<P>
Processing services, including payroll, claims and credit card
processing, have been the most popular outsourcing activity,
according to the IDC. In 1998, this activity claimed almost 60
percent of all outsourcing spending worldwide with 59.5 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Information systems outsourcing, which includes data center,
client/server, and help desk applications, is the fastest-growing
segment of the market. In the United States, information systems
outsourcing services will largely be driven by small and
medium-sized companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
