<HEADLINE> Italian Central Bank Governor Urges Reform on Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 8 (Xinhua) -- Antonio Fazio, governor of the Bank of
Italy, the Italian central bank, said Thursday that a reform of
the Italian pension system earlier rather than later was
indispensable if difficulties midway through the next decade were
to be avoided.
</P>
<P>
Reporting to the House and Senate budget committees, he said
that early reform of the pension system "is the premise for a
rapid and incisive lowering of the fiscal burden and for an
increase in investment spending."
</P>
<P>
He said that innovations in the pension system must be careful
to avoid substantial differences in how the generations are
treated.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, complementary retirement schemes should be
encouraged, he said.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the level of fiscal pressure in Italy, Fazio said it
is in line with the euro area's average.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he admitted that those Italians who pay their
taxes labor under a heavy fiscal burden.
</P>
<P>
A real and lasting tax cut for families and for businesses is
definitely required, he said.
</P>
<P>
As to the government's economic planning document approved by
government last week, Fazio said it would have been opportune to
have set a balanced budget as the goal "at least for the year
2002" and not 2003. 
</P>
