<HEADLINE> New Zealand Says "No" to Nuke Shipments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 9 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government is
concerned that two lightly armed ships carrying enough plutonium
to build 60 nuclear weapons may travel through the Tasman Sea on
their way from Europe to Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Dominion Friday reported that the ships, whose departure
from Britain is believed to be imminent, will carry MOX fuel, a
mixture of uranium and plutonium recycled from spent nuclear fuel.
</P>
<P>
The Wellington-based newspaper quoted a spokesman for NZ
Foreign Minister Don Mckinnon as saying that the NZ government has
expressed concern to Japan and that the ships should not approach
New Zealand waters.
</P>
<P>
"We do not know which of the three possible routes -- the
Panama Canal, South America, or South Africa-Tasman Sea-southeast
Pacific -- will be used," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"We have repeatedly stated that we would want all shipments of
nuclear material to stay as far away from New Zealand as possible.
Our missions in London, Paris and Tokyo have made a number of
diplomatic representations to underline the fact that the MOX
shipment would not be welcome here," he stressed.  
</P>
